left\"|[[Chicago Sky]]||0||1||1||-||style=\"text-align:left\"|[[2014 WNBA Finals|2014]]\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left\"|[[San Antonio Stars]] <small>(now Las Vegas Aces)</small> ||0||1||1||-||style=\"text-align:left\"|[[2008 WNBA Finals|2008]]\n|-style=\"background: #ffdfdf;\"\n|style=\"text-align:left\"|[[Charlotte Sting]] <small>(folded in 2006)</small>||0||1||1||-||style=\"text-align:left\"|[[2001 WNBA Finals|2001]]\n|}\n\nFormer teams that have no [[WNBA Finals]] appearances: \n*[[Cleveland Rockers]] (1997\u20132003)\n*[[Miami Sol]] (2000\u20132002) \n*[[Portland Fire]] (2000\u20132002)\n\n==Players and coaches==\n{{Main|List of Women's National Basketball Association players|List of Women's National Basketball Association head coaches}}\n{{see also|List of foreign WNBA players}}\n[[File:WNBA Sue Bird cropped.jpg|right|thumb|200px|[[Sue Bird]], a member of the [[WNBA's All-Decade Team|All-Decade]], [[WNBA's Top 15 Team|Top 15]], and [[WNBA Top 20@20|Top 20]] teams]]\nIn 2011, a decade and a half after the launch of the WNBA, only two players remained from the league's [[1997 WNBA season|inaugural season in 1997]]: [[Sheryl Swoopes]] and [[Tina Thompson]]. [[Lisa Leslie]] was the longest-tenured player from the 1997 draft class; she spent her entire career (1997\u20132009) with the [[Los Angeles Sparks]]. [[Sue Bird]] holds both of the league's most significant longevity records\u2014number of seasons in the league (16) and games played (508).\n\nThe members of the [[WNBA's All-Decade Team]] were chosen in 2006 on the occasion of the tenth anniversary of the WNBA from amongst 30 nominees compiled by fans, media, coach, and player voting. The team was to comprise the 10 best and most influential players of the first decade of the WNBA, with consideration also given to sportsmanship, community service, leadership, and contribution to the growth of women's basketball.\n\nPlayers for the [[WNBA's Top 15 Team]] were chosen in 2011 on the anniversary of the league's fifteenth season from amongst 30 nominees compiled similarly to that of the All-Decade Team process. This process was repeated for the league's 20th anniversary season in 2016 with the selection of the [[WNBA Top 20@20]].\n\nOver [[WNBA Career Scoring|30 players]] have scored at least 3,000 points in their WNBA careers. Only nine WNBA players have reached the 6,000 point milestone: Diana Taurasi, Tina Thompson, Tamika Catchings, Cappie Pondexter, Katie Smith, Lisa Leslie, Sue Bird, Candice Dupree, and Lauren Jackson. The scoring average leader is [[Cynthia Cooper-Dyke|Cynthia Cooper]], who averaged 21.0 points per game<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/wnba/leaders/pts_per_g_career.html |title=WNBA Career Leaders and Records for Points Per Game |website=Basketball-Reference.com |accessdate=August 28, 2018}}</ref> in five seasons with the Houston Comets (1997\u20132000, 2003).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/wnba/players/c/coopecy01w.html |title=Cynthia Cooper WNBA Stats |website=Basketball-Reference.com |accessdate=August 29, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2007, [[Paul Westhead]] of the [[Phoenix Mercury]] became the first person to earn both NBA and WNBA championship rings as a coach.\n\nIn 2008, 50-year-old [[Nancy Lieberman]] became the oldest player to play in a WNBA game. She signed a seven-day contract with the [[Detroit Shock]] and played one game, tallying [https://web.archive.org/web/20080912150859/http://www.wnba.com/games/20080724/DETHOU/boxscore.html two assists and two turnovers] in nine minutes of action. By playing in the one game Lieberman broke a record that she had set in 1997 when she was the league's oldest player at 39.\n\nSue Bird, who has played for the Seattle Storm since 2002, holds the record for career assists<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/wnba/leaders/ast_career.html |title=WNBA Career Leaders and Records for Assists |website=Basketball-Reference.com |accessdate=August 28, 2018}}</ref> with 2,831 in 508 regular-season games.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/wnba/players/b/birdsu01w.html |title=Sue Bird WNBA Stats |website=Basketball-Reference.com |accessdate=August 28, 2018}}</ref> The record for most assists per game is currently held by [[Courtney Vandersloot]], an American who also holds a Hungarian passport and represents [[Hungary women's national basketball team|that country]] internationally. She has averaged 6.17 assists per game during her career with the Chicago Sky (2011\u2013present).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/wnba/leaders/ast_per_g_career.html |title=WNBA Career Leaders and Records for Assists Per Game |website=Basketball-Reference.com |accessdate=September 15, 2019}}</ref> Vandersloot also has the top three seasons in assists per game, with 8.1 in 2017, 8.6 in 2018, and 9.1 in 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/wnba/leaders/ast_per_g_season.html |title=WNBA Single Season Leaders and Records for Assists Per Game |website=Basketball-Reference.com |accessdate=September 15, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Milestones ===\n{{see also|WNBA records}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin:1em auto;\"\n|-\n|+ WNBA Milestones\n|-\n!Milestone\n!Player\n!Team\n!Date\n!Information\n|-\n| First player signed\n| [[Sheryl Swoopes]]\n| [[Houston Comets]]\n| October 23, 1996\n| Signed by the WNBA and assigned to [[Houston Comets|Houston]].\n|-\n| First points scored\n| [[Penny Toler]]\n| [[Los Angeles Sparks]]\n| June 21, 1997\n| Scored the first points on a baseline jump-shot.\n|-\n| First triple-double\n| [[Sheryl Swoopes]]\n| [[Houston Comets]]\n| July 27, 1998\n| 14 points, 15 rebounds, 10 assists\n|-\n| First goaltending call\n| [[Sylvia Fowles]]\n| [[Chicago Sky]]\n| June 3, 2008\n| Trying to block a layup by [[Lisa Leslie]].\n|-\n| First slam dunk\n| [[Lisa Leslie]]\n| [[Los Angeles Sparks]]\n| July 30, 2002\n| Dunked on a fast break against [[Miami Sol|Miami]]\n|-\n| First [[50\u201340\u201390 club|50\u201340\u201390 season]]\n| [[Elena Delle Donne]]\n| [[Washington Mystics]]\n| 2019\n| 51.5% FG, 43.0% 3FG, 97.4% FT<ref name=\"EDD 50\u201340\u201390\"/>\n|-\n| Most career points\n| [[Diana Taurasi]]\n| [[Phoenix Mercury]]\n| 2004\u20132014, 2016\u2013present\n| 8,549 points\n|-\n| Most career rebounds\n| [[Rebekkah Brunson]]\n| [[Sacramento Monarchs]] / [[Minnesota Lynx]]\n| 2004\u20132019\n| 3,356 rebounds\n|-\n| Most career assists\n| [[Sue Bird]]\n| [[Seattle Storm]]\n| 2002\u20132012, 2014\u2013present\n| 2,831 assists\n|-\n| Most 3-pointers\n| [[Diana Taurasi]]\n| [[Phoenix Mercury]]\n| 2004\u20132014, 2016\u2013present\n| 1,102 3-pointers\n|-\n| Most points in a game\n| [[Liz Cambage]]\n| [[Dallas Wings]]\n| July 17, 2018\n| 53 points\n|-\n| Most rebounds in a game\n| [[Chamique Holdsclaw]]\n| [[Washington Mystics]]\n| May 23, 2003\n| 24 rebounds\n|-\n| Most assists in a game\n| [[Ticha Penicheiro]]\n| [[Sacramento Monarchs]]\n| July 29, 1998 &<br />August 3, 2002\n| 16 assists\n|-\n| Most career wins for a coach\n| [[Mike Thibault]]\n| [[Connecticut Sun]] / [[Washington Mystics]]<ref>http://www.wnba.com/mystics/news/mike_thibault_070613.html</ref>\n| 2003\u2013present\n| 336 wins\n|-\n| Most team points in one game\n| -\n| [[Phoenix Mercury]]\n| July 24, 2010\n| 127 points in double overtime against [[Minnesota Lynx|Minnesota]]\n|-\n| Most team points in a regulation game\n| -\n| [[Phoenix Mercury]]\n| July 22, 2010\n| 123 points against [[Tulsa Shock|Tulsa]]\n|-\n| Largest margin of victory\n| -\n| [[Seattle Storm]]\n| August 7, 2010\n| 46-point win (111\u201365) over [[Tulsa Shock|Tulsa]]\n|-\n| Largest attendance for one game\n| -\n| [[Detroit Shock]]\n| September 16, 2007\n| 22,076 in game 5 of [[2007 WNBA Finals|2007 Finals]]\n|}\n\n===Awards===\nAround the beginning of September (or late August in Olympic and [[FIBA Women's Basketball World Cup|FIBA World Cup]] years), the regular season ends. It is during this time that voting begins for individual awards. The [[WNBA Sixth Woman of the Year Award|Sixth Woman of the Year Award]] is given to the best player coming off the bench (must have more games coming off the bench than actual games started).<ref name=WNBA6th>{{cite web|url=http://www.wnba.com/news/awards07_sixth.html|title=Detroit's Plenette Pierson Named 2007 WNBA Sixth Woman of the Year|publisher=WNBA}}</ref> The [[WNBA Rookie of the Year Award|Rookie of the Year Award]] is awarded to the most outstanding first-year player. The [[WNBA Most Improved Player Award|Most Improved Player Award]] is awarded to the player who is deemed to have shown the most improvement from the previous season. The [[WNBA Defensive Player of the Year Award|Defensive Player of the Year Award]] is awarded to the league's best defender. The [[Kim Perrot Sportsmanship Award]] is awarded to the player who shows outstanding sportsmanship on and off the court. The [[WNBA Coach of the Year Award|Coach of the Year Award]] is awarded to the coach that has made the most positive difference to a team. The [[WNBA Most Valuable Player Award|Most Valuable Player Award]] is given to the player deemed the most valuable for her team that season. The newest WNBA award is the [[WNBA Basketball Executive of the Year Award|Basketball Executive of the Year Award]], first presented in 2017 to the team executive most instrumental in his or her team's success in that season.\n\nAlso named are the [[All-WNBA Teams]], the [[WNBA All-Defensive Team|All-Defensive Teams]], and the [[WNBA All-Rookie Team|All-Rookie Team]]; each consists of five players. There are two All-WNBA teams, consisting of the top players at each position, with the first-team status being the most desirable. There are two All-Defensive teams, consisting of the top defenders at each position. There is one All-Rookie team, consisting of the top first-year players regardless of position.\n\n====Most recent award winners====\nWinners are from the most recent season unless otherwise indicated.\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width: 85%; margin:1em auto;\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"width:155px;\"|Award\n!width=125|Winner\n!width=100|Position\n!width=135|Team\n!width=115|Votes/Statistic{{efn|\"Votes\" are listed as first-place votes, although the winners for all WNBA awards apart from the statistically based Peak Performer Awards are determined by points earned rather than first-place votes.}}\n|-\n|colspan=2| '''[[WNBA Most Valuable Player Award|Most Valuable Player Award]]'''\n| [[Elena Delle Donne]]\n| Guard\u2013forward\n| [[Washington Mystics]]\n| 41 out of 43\n|-\n|colspan=2| '''[[WNBA Finals MVP Award|Finals MVP Award]]'''\n| [[Emma Meesseman]]\n| Center\n| [[Washington Mystics]]\n| \n|-\n|colspan=2| '''[[WNBA Rookie of the Year Award|Rookie of the Year Award]]'''\n| [[Napheesa Collier]]\n| Forward\n| [[Minnesota Lynx]]\n| 29 out of 43\n|-\n|colspan=2| '''[[WNBA Most Improved Player Award|Most Improved Player Award]]'''\n| [[Leilani Mitchell]]\n| Guard\n| [[Phoenix Mercury]]\n| 27 out of 43\n|-\n|colspan=2| '''[[WNBA Defensive Player of the Year Award|Defensive Player of the Year Award]]'''\n| [[Natasha Howard (basketball)|Natasha Howard]]\n| Forward\n| [[Seattle Storm]]\n| 33 out of 43\n|-\n|colspan=2| '''[[WNBA Sixth Woman of the Year Award|Sixth Woman of the Year Award]]'''\n| [[Dearica Hamby]] \n| Forward\n| [[Las Vegas Aces]]\n| 41 out of 43\n|-\n|colspan=2| '''[[Kim Perrot Sportsmanship Award]]'''\n| [[Nneka Ogwumike]]\n| Forward\n| [[Los Angeles Sparks]]\n| 7 out of 43\n|-\n|colspan=2| '''[[WNBA Peak Performers|Peak Performer: Points]]'''\n| [[Brittney Griner]]\n| Center\n| [[Phoenix Mercury]]\n| 20.7 PPG\n|-\n|colspan=2| '''[[WNBA Peak Performers|Peak Performer: Rebounds]]'''\n| [[Jonquel Jones]]\n| Center\n| [[Connecticut Sun]]\n| 9.7 RPG\n|-\n|colspan=2| '''[[WNBA Peak Performers|Peak Performer: Assists]]'''\n| [[Courtney Vandersloot]]\n| Guard\n| [[Chicago Sky]]\n| 9.1 APG{{efn|WNBA record.<ref name=\"EDD 50\u201340\u201390\">{{cite news|url=https://www.espn.com/wnba/story/_/id/27573501/delle-donne-first-wnba-join-50-40-90-club |title=Delle Donne first in WNBA to join 50-40-90 club |website=ESPN.com |date=September 8, 2019 |accessdate=September 9, 2019}}</ref>}}\n|-\n|colspan=2| '''[[WNBA Coach of the Year Award|Coach of the Year Award]]'''\n| [[James Wade (basketball)|James Wade]]\n| Coach\n| [[Chicago Sky]]\n| 27 out of 43\n|-\n|colspan=2| '''[[WNBA Basketball Executive of the Year Award|Basketball Executive of the Year Award]]'''\n| [[Cheryl Reeve]]\n| General manager\n| [[Minnesota Lynx]]\n| 4 out of 11\n|}\n\n;Notes\n{{notelist|group=award}}\n\n====Retired numbers====\n[[File: Lauren Jackson 2a.JPG|thumb|right|160px|Lauren Jackson, one of the most notable players in WNBA history. Number 15 was retired by Seattle Storm in her honour.]]\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! width=40px|No.\n! width=150px|Team\n! width=150px|Player\n! width=40px|Pos.\n! width=100px|Tenure{{efn|group=note|Reflects tenure with the team that retired the player's number; not necessarily identical to the player's WNBA tenure.}}\n! width=40px|Ref.\n|-\n| '''9''' || rowspan=2|[[Los Angeles Sparks]] || {{sortname|Lisa|Leslie}} || [[Center (basketball)|C]] || 1997\u20132009 || <ref>[http://www.espn.com/news/story?id=5450577 Sparks to retire Lisa Leslie's jersey] on ESPN, 9 Aug 2010</ref><ref>[http://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/sdut-la-sparks-to-retire-lisa-leslies-jersey-2010aug09-story.html LA Sparks to retire Lisa Leslie's jersey], ''The San Diego Union Tribune'', 9 Aug 2010</ref>\n|-\n| '''11''' || {{sortname|Penny|Toler}} || [[Guard (basketball)|G]] || 1997\u201399 || <ref>[http://www.wnba.com/archive/wnba/sparks/news/jersey_toler_060717.html Sparks Retire Toler\u2019s Jersey] on WNBA.com</ref>\n|-\n| '''24''' || [[Indiana Fever]] || {{sortname|Tamika|Catchings}} || [[Small forward|SF]] || 2002\u201316 || <ref>[https://utsports.com/news/2017/6/26/Indiana_Fever_to_Retire_Catchings_No_24_Jersey.aspx?path=wbball INDIANA FEVER TO RETIRE CATCHINGS' NO. 24 JERSEY] on Tennessee Athletics website, 26 Jun 2017</ref>\n|-\n|'''25''' || [[Las Vegas Aces]] || {{sortname|Becky|Hammon}} {{refn|Number retired by the franchise when it was playing as the [[San Antonio Stars]]. Hammon played the last eight seasons of her WNBA career in San Antonio.|group=note|name=becky}} || G || 2007\u201314 || <ref>{{cite web|title=Stars Retire Becky Hammon\u2019s Jersey|url=http://stars.wnba.com/news/stars-retire-becky-hammons-jersey/|publisher=WNBA|date=June 27, 2016|accessdate=June 28, 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n| '''13''' || [[Minnesota Lynx]] || {{sortname|Lindsay|Whalen}} || [[Guard (basketball)|G]] || 2004\u201318 || <ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espn.com/wnba/story/_/id/26552356/lynx-honor-whalen-first-retired-number |title=Lynx to honor Whalen with first retired number |agency=Associated Press |website=ESPN.com |date=April 18, 2019 |accessdate=April 18, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| '''7''' || rowspan=4|[[Phoenix Mercury]] || {{sortname|Michele|Timms}} || [[Guard (basketball)|G]] || 1997\u20132001 || <ref>[http://www.wnba.com/archive/wnba/mercury/news/reitre7_020730.html Mercury to retired #7] on WNBA.com</ref><ref>[https://www.sahof.org.au/hall-of-fame/member-profile/?memberID=360&memberType=athlete Michelle Timms] on Sports Australia HoF</ref>\n|-\n| '''13''' || {{sortname|Penny|Taylor}} || [[Swingman|G/F]] || 2004\u201316 || <ref>[Phoenix Mercury retires Penny Taylor's jersey as Australian greats pay tribute] by Roy Ward on ''The Sydney Morning Herald'', 10 July 2017</ref>\n|-\n| '''22''' || {{sortname|Jennifer|Gillom}} || [[Forward (basketball)|F]] || 1997\u20132002 || \n|-\n| '''32''' || {{sortname|Bridget|Pettis}} || [[Guard (basketball)|G]] || 1997\u20132006 || \n|-\n| '''15''' || [[Seattle Storm]] || {{sortname|Lauren|Jackson}} || [[Forward-center|F/C]] || 2001\u201312 || <ref>[http://www.espn.com/wnba/story/_/id/17088555/seattle-storm-retire-lauren-jackson-jersey-give-send-deserved Storm retire jersey, finally able to give Lauren Jackson send-off she deserved] by Kevin Pelton on ESPN, 18 Jul 2016</ref><ref>[https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/wnba/2016/07/16/seattle-storm-retire-lauren-jacksons-no-15-jersey/87170538/ Seattle Storm retire Aussie Lauren Jackson's No. 15 jersey], USA Today, 16 Jul 2016</ref>\n|}\n\n;Notes\n{{Reflist|group=note}}\n\n====Pending number retirements====\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! width=40px|No.\n! width=150px|Team\n! width=150px|Player\n! width=40px|Pos.\n! width=100px|Tenure\n! width=80px | Retirement date\n! width=40px|Ref.\n|-\n| '''32''' || [[Minnesota Lynx]] || {{sortname|Rebekkah|Brunson}} || [[Forward (basketball)|F]] || 2010\u201319 || TBA || <ref>{{cite press release|url=https://www.wnba.com/news/minnesota-lynx-hire-five-time-wnba-champion-rebekkah-brunson-as-assistant-coach/ |title=Minnesota Lynx Hire Five-Time WNBA Champion Rebekkah Brunson as Assistant Coach |publisher=WNBA |date=February 11, 2020 |accessdate=February 11, 2020}}</ref>\n|}\n\n===Notable international players===\n{{further|List of foreign WNBA players}}\nA number of international players that have played in the WNBA have earned multiple all-stars or won MVP awards:\n* {{flagicon|Russia}} [[Elena Baranova]], Russia \u2013 the first international player in the WNBA ([[1997 WNBA season|1997]]), one-time All-Star ([[2001 WNBA All-Star Game|2001]]).\n* {{flagicon|Australia}} [[Lauren Jackson]], Australia \u2013 two-time champion ([[2004 WNBA Finals|2004]], [[2010 WNBA Finals|2010]]), three-time [[WNBA MVP|MVP]] and eight-time [[WNBA All-Star Game|All-Star]]\n* {{flagicon|Portugal}} [[Ticha Penicheiro]], Portugal \u2013 won a championship with the [[Sacramento Monarchs|Monarchs]] in [[2005 WNBA Finals|2005]] and four-time [[WNBA All-Star Game|All-Star]]\n* {{flagicon|Australia}} [[Penny Taylor]], Australia \u2013 three-time champion ([[2007 WNBA Finals|2007]], [[2009 WNBA Finals|2009]], [[2014 WNBA Finals|2014]]) and four-time [[WNBA All-Star Game|All-Star]]\n* {{flagicon|Canada}} [[Tammy Sutton-Brown]], Canada \u2013 two-time [[WNBA All-Star Game|All-Star]]\n* {{flagicon|VCT}} [[Sophia Young]], [[Saint Vincent and the Grenadines]] \u2013 four-time [[WNBA All-Star Game|All-Star]]\n\nSome of these players, among them Penicheiro, Sutton-Brown, and Young played U.S. college basketball.\n\n==Rules and regulations==\nRules are governed by standard [[Basketball#Rules and regulations|basketball rules]] as defined by the NBA, with a few notable exceptions:\n* The three-point line is {{convert|22|ft|1.75|in|m|2|abbr=on}} from the center of the basket, with a distance of {{convert|22|ft|m|2|abbr=on}} at the corners. The main arc is essentially identical to that used by [[FIBA]] (effective October 1, 2012 for domestic competitions) and [[National Collegiate Athletics Association|NCAA men's]] play (effective in 2019\u201320 in Division I and 2020\u201321 in Divisions II and III). The WNBA corner distance, as measured from the center of the basket, is identical to that of the NBA; the FIBA and NCAA men's distance at the corners is {{convert|4|in|cm|2|abbr=on}} shorter.\n* The regulation WNBA ball is a minimum {{convert|28.5|in|cm}} in circumference and weighs {{convert|20.0|oz|g}}, {{convert|1|in|cm}} smaller and {{convert|2|oz|g}} lighter than the NBA ball. Since 2004, this size has been used for all senior-level women's competitions throughout the world in full-court basketball. Competitions in the half-court [[3x3 basketball|3x3]] variant used the women's ball until 2015, when a dedicated ball with the circumference of the women's ball but the weight of the men's ball was introduced.\n* Quarters are 10 minutes in duration instead of 12.\n\nGames are divided into four 10-minute quarters as opposed to the league's original two 20-minute halves of play, similar to FIBA and NCAA women's college rules (many WNBA players play in European, Chinese, or Australian leagues, which all use the FIBA rule set).\n\nA recent trend with new WNBA rules has been to match them with a similar NBA rule. Since the [[2006 WNBA season]]:<ref name=\"WNBA Announces Rule Changes for 2006\">{{cite web |url=http://www.wnba.com/news/rulechanges_051206.html |title=WNBA Announces Rule Changes for 2006 |date=December 6, 2005 |work=[[WNBA.com]] |accessdate=June 13, 2011}}</ref>\n* The winner of the opening jump ball shall begin the 4th quarter with the ball out of bounds. The loser shall begin with the ball out of bounds in the second and third quarters. Previously under the two-half format, both periods started with jump balls, presumably to eliminate the possibility of a team purposely losing the opening tip to gain the opening possession of the second half. This is not a problem under the four-quarters because the ''winner'' of the opening tip gets the opening possession of the final period.\n* The [[shot clock]] was decreased from 30 to 24 seconds. The rule changes signaled a move away from rules more similar to those of [[college basketball]] and toward those that provide a more NBA-like game. FIBA also uses a 24-second clock. Also, come 2020, last 5 seconds of the shot clock counts down in tenths of a second.\n\nThe [[2007 WNBA season]] brought changes that included:<ref name=\"WNBA Announces Rule Changes for 2007 Season\">{{cite web |url=http://www.wnba.com/news/newrules_release_070130.html |title=WNBA Announces Rule Changes for 2007 Season |date=January 30, 2007 |work=[[WNBA.com]] |accessdate=June 13, 2011}}</ref>\n* The amount of time that a team must move the ball across the half-court line went from 10 to 8 seconds.\n* A referee can grant time-outs to either a player or the coach.\n* Two free throws and possession of the ball for a clear-path-to-the-basket foul. Previously only one free throw was awarded as well as possession.\n\nIn [[2012 WNBA season|2012]], the WNBA added the block/charge arc under the basket. As of [[2013 WNBA season|2013]] the defensive three-second rule and anti-flopping guidelines were introduced. The three-point line was also extended; in 2017, that line extended into the corners to match the NBA's.\n\nSince [[2017 WNBA season|2017]], [[Tissot]] is the official timekeeper for the league, as it uses a unified game clock/shot clock system.\n\n===Court dimensions===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width: 60%; margin:1em auto;\"\n|-\n!colspan=3|WNBA Court Dimensions\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! Area\n! Imperial\n! Metric\n|-\n|Length of court (baseline to baseline) || 94&nbsp;ft || 28.65 m\n|-\n|Width of court (sideline to sideline) || 50&nbsp;ft || 15.24 m\n|-\n|Rim height (floor to rim) || 10&nbsp;ft || 3.05 m\n|-\n|Center circle diameter || 12&nbsp;ft || 3.66 m\n|-\n|Three-point line distance from center of basket || 22&nbsp;ft 1.75&nbsp;in || 6.75 m\n|-\n|3-point line distance from center of basket (corners) || 22&nbsp;ft || 6.61 m\n|-\n|Shaded area/Lane/Key length || 19&nbsp;ft || 5.8 m\n|-\n|Shaded area/Lane/Key width || 16&nbsp;ft || 4.88 m\n|-\n|Restricted area (aka \"block/charge arc\")<br />(distance from center of basket) || 4&nbsp;ft || 1.22 m\n|-\n|Free-throw line (distance from backboard) || 15&nbsp;ft || 4.57 m\n|-\n|Free-throw half-circle radius || 6&nbsp;ft || 1.83 m\n|-\n|Backboard width (side to side) || 6&nbsp;ft || 1.83 m\n|-\n|Coaching box width (from baseline) || 28&nbsp;ft || 8.54 m\n|-\n|colspan=3|''*All dimensions are in line with [[National Basketball Association|NBA]] regulations except the main three-point arc. The three-point distance at the corners is identical in the NBA and WNBA.''\n|}\n\n==Business==\n\n===Finance===\nThe WNBA is not able to support itself. During the mid-2000s, the NBA spent more than $10 million per year to keep the WNBA financially solvent.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehoya.com/wnba-fails-to-thrill-fans/|title=WNBA Fails to Thrill Fans|date=October 15, 2012|publisher=The Hoya|accessdate=April 15, 2013}}</ref> In 2007, teams were estimated to be losing $1.5 million to $2 million a year.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/basketball/wnba/2007-06-11-new-owners_N.htm|title=New owners stake claim in overhauling WNBA|last=Lieber Steeg|first=Jill |date=June 12, 2007|work=[[USA Today]]|accessdate=June 13, 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe league has begun to do better financially in recent years. In December 2010, Donna Orender said that the league had its first-ever \"cash flow positive\" team (Connecticut Sun) for the 2010 season.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/sports_blog/2010/12/donna-orender-david-stern-on-wnba.html|title=Donna Orender, David Stern on WNBA|date=December 3, 2010|work=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=November 7, 2015|first=Melissa|last=Rohlin}}</ref> In 2011, three teams were profitable, and in 2013, six of the league's 12 teams reported a profit.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.sportsmediawatch.com/2014/02/no-the-wnba-is-not-a-major-sport-and-thats-fine/| title=No, the WNBA is Not a Major Sport (And That's Fine) | author=Paulsen | date=February 28, 2014 | accessdate=November 7, 2015 | publisher=Sports Media Watch}}</ref> The league has also signed extended television contracts with ESPN and sponsorship agreements with [[Boost Mobile]].\n\n===Activism===\nAs the popularity of the league has grown, players have gained more voice and power to perform as activists in many fields. One of the activist players' main focuses is the inequality between men's and women's sports. Many players such as Brittney Grinner, Breanna Stewart, and Maya Moore have spoken about equality between gender, sexual orientation, and race.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.swishappeal.com/2018/5/1/17305038/2018-wnba-hoops-happenings-womens-basketball-nike-uniforms-breanna-stewart-wild-feminist-sue-bird\n|title=Hoops Happening: Today in women\u2019s basketball|date=May 1, 2018|publisher= Tamryn Spruill| accessdate=September 15, 2018}}</ref> The players have also supported progressive social and political movements such as [[Black Lives Matter]] and others.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Shoichet |first1=Catherine E. |last2=Martin |first2=Jill |title=Off-duty cops walkout over WNBA players' Black Lives Matter shirts |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2016/07/12/us/wnba-minnesota-lynx-black-lives-matter-shirts/index.html |publisher=[[CNN]] |accessdate=29 December 2018 |date=12 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Sponsorships===\nOn June 1, 2009, the [[Phoenix Mercury]] was the first team in WNBA history to announce a marquee sponsorship. The team secured a partnership with [[LifeLock]] to brand their jerseys and warm-ups.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wnba.com/mercury/news/lifelock_release_090601.html |title=Mercury, LifeLock Break New Ground with Partnership |date=June 1, 2009 |publisher=[[WNBA.com]] |accessdate=June 13, 2011}}</ref> It was the first branded jersey in WNBA history. Following the expiration of the LifeLock deal, the Mercury secured a new uniform sponsorship deal with [[Casino Arizona]] and [[Talking Stick Resort]] on February 3, 2014.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wnba.com/news/mercury_new_partnership_02032014.html |title=Phoenix Mercury Announces Marquee Partnership with Casino Arizona and Talking Stick Resort |date=February 3, 2014 |publisher=[[WNBA.com]] |accessdate=May 16, 2014}}</ref>\n\nOther teams eventually followed in the Mercury's footsteps to bring the total to 11 current teams with sponsorship deals right in front of their jerseys and some teams have sponsors on the upper left-hand shoulder:\n*'''[[Chicago Sky]]''' \u2013 front: [[University of Chicago Medical Center|University of Chicago Medicine]] & upper-left: [[Magellan Corporation]]; team was formerly sponsored by [[Magellan Corporation]]\n*'''[[Connecticut Sun]]''' \u2013 Front: [[Mohegan Sun]] & upper-left: [[Yale-New Haven Health System]]; team was formerly sponsored by [[Frontier Communications]]\n*'''[[Dallas Wings]]''' \u2013 front: [[Texas Capital Bank]] & upper-left: Arlington Convention & Visitor Bureau; team was formerly sponsored by [[American Fidelity Assurance]]\n*'''[[Indiana Fever]]''' \u2013 [[Salesforce.com]]; team was formerly sponsored by [[Finish Line, Inc.]]\n*'''[[Las Vegas Aces]]''' \u2013 upper-left: [[MGM Resorts International]]\n*'''[[New York Liberty]]''' \u2013 upper-left: [[Hospital for Special Surgery]]; team was formerly sponsored by [[DraftKings]]\n*'''[[Los Angeles Sparks]]''' \u2013 front: EquiTrust Life Insurance; team was formerly sponsored by [[Farmers Insurance]]\n*'''[[Minnesota Lynx]]''' \u2013 front: [[Mayo Clinic]] & upper-left: [[Sharecare]]\n*'''[[Phoenix Mercury]]''' \u2013 front: [[Casino Arizona]] and [[Talking Stick Resort]] & upper-left: [[PayPal]]\n*'''[[Seattle Storm]]''' \u2013 front: [[Swedish Medical Center]] & upper-left: [[Symetra]]; team was formerly sponsored by [[Bing (search engine)|Bing]]\n*'''[[Washington Mystics]]''' \u2013 front: [[GEICO]]; team was formerly sponsored by [[Inova Health System]]\n\nThe now-relocated [[Tulsa Shock]] (Osage Casino) and [[San Antonio Stars]] ([[H-E-B]]) had jersey sponsorships at one time.\n\nOn August 22, 2011, the WNBA announced a league-wide marquee sponsorship with [[Boost Mobile]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wnba.com/news/boost_partnership_110822.html |title=Boost Mobile and WNBA Form First-Ever Leaguewide Marquee Sponsorship |date=August 22, 2011 |publisher=[[WNBA.com]] |accessdate=August 22, 2011}}</ref> The deal would allow the Boost Mobile logo to be placed on eleven of the 12 teams' jerseys (excluding San Antonio) in addition to branding on the courts and in arenas. A source said the deal is a \"multiyear, eight-figure deal\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sportsbusinessdaily.com/Journal/Issues/2011/08/22/Marketing-and-Sponsorship/WNBA-Boost.aspx |title=WNBA lands Boost Mobile as top sponsor |date=August 22, 2011 |publisher=Sports Business Journal |accessdate=August 22, 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn March 14, 2016, the WNBA completed a deal with Verizon Wireless to place its name on the front of 10 of 12 team jerseys, excluding the Stars and Sun, as well as in-arena advertising, and reserved commercial space during WNBA broadcasts. The deal also includes the sponsorship of the All-Star Game, Inspiring Women Luncheon, and other unspecified events, but not the Monthly and Yearly Awards.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sportsbusinessdaily.com/Journal/Issues/2016/03/14/Marketing-and-Sponsorship/WNBA-Verizon.aspx|title=Verizon stakes out space on WNBA jerseys|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nOn March 28, the league introduced new uniforms bearing the new Verizon sponsor name, which eliminated white jerseys and made the secondary color a basis for a uniform. The jersey font remained unchanged, as well as the primary color used for the away uniform. Teams can use either jersey for home and away games. Pictures of the jerseys can be viewed on the WNBA website.\n\nIn 2009, the Phoenix Mercury became the first American professional basketball team to feature advertisements on their uniform, when they sold an ad to LifeLock Insurance on the front of their jerseys, leading many people to wonder if ads on NBA uniforms were coming soon. Since then several other WNBA teams have followed suit. The NBA announced in the summer of 2016 that they will begin to feature advertisements on jerseys, with the first team to do so being the Philadelphia 76ers (with a StubHub sticker now on their jerseys).\nBefore the start of the 2011 season, every team announced a new look for their uniforms. The supplier of the uniforms for the league, [[Adidas]], upgraded all teams to new high-tech designs, much like they did for the NBA before the start of their season.\n\nOn April 8, 2019, the WNBA announced a multiyear marquee partnership with [[AT&T]], making them the first non-apparel partner to have its logo featured on the front of all 12 team jerseys. The jerseys officially debuted during the [[2019 WNBA draft]].<ref>{{cite web |title=AT&T and WNBA Announce Landmark Marquee Partnership |url=https://www.wnba.com/news/att-and-wnba-announce-landmark-marquee-partnership/ |website=WNBA.com |accessdate=May 23, 2019 |date=April 8, 2019}}</ref>\n\nSponsorships have come from major companies such as Boost Mobile and Farmers Insurance. Pepsi and Nike have also partnered up with the WNBA.\n\nAs of the [[2019 WNBA season]], the [[Atlanta Dream]] are the only team with no team sponsors.\n\n===Salaries, rosters, and collective bargaining===\nBefore the 2009 season, the maximum team roster size was changed from 13 players (11 active and 2 inactive) to 11 players (all active). Any team that falls below nine players able to play due to injury or any other factor outside of the control of the team will, upon request, be granted a roster hardship exception allowing the team to sign an additional player or players so that the team will have nine players able to play in an upcoming game or games. As soon as the injured (or otherwise sidelined) player(s) can play, the roster hardship player(s)\u2014not any other player on the roster\u2014must be waived.\nIn March 2014, the WNBA and players signed a new, 8-year collective bargaining agreement, increasing the number of players on a roster to 12.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/wnba/story/_/id/10565327/wnba-players-union-agree-8-year-collective-bargaining-agreement|title=WNBA, players' union agree to 8-year CBA|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nThe [[WNBA Draft]] is held annually every spring. The minimum age is 22 years for American players and 20 years for international players, measured as of December 31 of the calendar year of the draft. The draft is three rounds long, with each of the 12 teams in the league (trades aside) getting three picks each. The draft order for the eight teams that made the playoffs the previous year are based on team records, and the team with the highest previous record will pick last. For the remaining top four picks, a selection process similar to the [[NBA Draft Lottery]] is conducted for the four teams that did not qualify for the playoffs.\n\nPreviously, in 2008, a new six-year collective bargaining agreement was agreed upon between the players and the league. The [[salary cap]] for an entire team in 2010 was $827,000 (although it was later lowered to $775,000). By 2013 (the sixth year under this agreement), the cap for an entire team was $900,000. In 2010, the ''minimum'' salary for a player with three-plus years of experience was $51,000 while the ''maximum'' salary for a six-plus year player was $101,500 (the first time in league history that players can receive over $100,000). The minimum salary for rookies was $35,190.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://womensbasketballonline.com/wnba/rosters/salary.html|title=Women's basketball salary|access-date=2013-03-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130801060900/http://womensbasketballonline.com/wnba/rosters/salary.html|archive-date=2013-08-01|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.womensbasketballonline.com/wnba/wnbacba08.pdf|title=Women's basketball 2008|access-date=2013-03-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130801064634/http://www.womensbasketballonline.com/wnba/wnbacba08.pdf|archive-date=2013-08-01|url-status=dead}}</ref> Many WNBA players supplement their salaries by playing in European, [[Women's National Basketball League|Australian]], or more recently [[Women's Chinese Basketball Association|Chinese]] women's basketball leagues during the WNBA off-season. The WNBA has been criticized for [[gender pay gap|paying female players less]] than their NBA counterparts, although this is attributed to the much greater revenues of the NBA.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://sports.vice.com/en_us/article/basketballs-gender-wage-gap-is-even-worse-than-you-think |title=Basketball's Gender Wage Gap Is Even Worse Than You Think |publisher=VICE Sports |date=12 August 2015 |last1=Berri |first1=David |accessdate=5 April 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160406131910/https://sports.vice.com/en_us/article/basketballs-gender-wage-gap-is-even-worse-than-you-think |archivedate=6 April 2016 }}</ref>\n\nThe decision of superstar [[Diana Taurasi]] to sit out the 2015 WNBA season was seen by some in the media as a harbinger of salary-related troubles in the future. The Russian club for which she was playing at the time, [[UMMC Ekaterinburg]], offered her a bonus well over the league's salary cap to sit out that season. Taurasi accepted, largely because she had not had an offseason since playing college basketball more than a decade earlier. Such offers have often been made to star American players, including Taurasi herself, but none were accepted until Taurasi did so in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/wnba/story/_/id/12272036/diana-taurasi-decision-sit-spark-wnba-salary-changes |title=Diana Taurasi's decision to sit out should spark WNBA salary changes |first=Kate |last=Fagan |publisher=ESPN.com |date=February 4, 2015 |accessdate=September 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\nA more recent incident that led to widespread media comment on the WNBA's salary structure was the [[Achilles tendon rupture|torn]] [[Achilles tendon|Achilles]] suffered by reigning WNBA MVP [[Breanna Stewart]] while playing for another Russian side, [[Dynamo Kursk]], in the [[2018\u201319 EuroLeague Women|2019 EuroLeague Women final]]. The injury came at a time when the WNBA and its players' union were preparing to negotiate a new collective bargaining agreement,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://grandstandcentral.com/2018/sports/basketball/yes-the-wnba-wage-gap-is-real/ |title=Yes, the WNBA Wage Gap is a Real Thing |first=Al |last=Neal |publisher=Grandstand Central |date=July 13, 2018 |accessdate=July 1, 2019}}</ref> following the union's announcement on November 2018 that it would opt out of the current CBA after the 2019 season. With overseas leagues offering much higher salaries to many players than the WNBA currently provides, roughly 70% of the league's players go overseas in any given season. While these players do not necessarily play as many games as NBA players do in their seasons, even participants in the NBA Finals get several months of rest in the offseason, something not available for WNBA players who also play overseas.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.seattletimes.com/sports/storm/breanna-stewarts-achilles-injury-underscores-need-for-wnba-to-find-solution-to-pay-issue/ |title=Breanna Stewart\u2019s Achilles injury underscores need for WNBA to find solution to pay issue |first=Larry |last=Stone |newspaper=The Seattle Times |date=April 19, 2019 |accessdate=April 26, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.azcentral.com/story/sports/wnba/mercury/2019/04/14/breanna-stewart-injury-have-major-impact-wnba-cba-talks/3470025002/ |title=WNBA star Breanna Stewart to miss season after Achilles injury in EuroLeague championship |first=Jeff |last=Metcalf |newspaper=Arizona Republic |date=April 14, 2019 |accessdate=April 26, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Voepel Stewie\">{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/wnba/story/_/id/26532729/could-breanna-stewart-injury-tipping-point-wnba-negotiations |title=Could Breanna Stewart's injury be tipping point in WNBA negotiations? |first=Mechelle |last=Voepel |website=ESPN.com |date=April 17, 2019 |accessdate=April 26, 2019}}</ref> In a story on the ramifications of Stewart's injury, Mechelle Voepel of ESPN had this to say about the lead-in to the injury:<ref name=\"Voepel Stewie\"/><blockquote> For Stewart, her 2018 went like this: playing in [[Women's Chinese Basketball Association|China]], brief time off, [[2018 WNBA season|WNBA season]], [[2018 FIBA Women's Basketball World Cup|World Cup]] in the Canary Islands, brief time off, playing in Russia. She hasn't had significant recovery time since before her [[2015\u201316 UConn Huskies women's basketball team|senior season]] at [[UConn Huskies women's basketball|UConn]]. Now, she'll have time away from playing but while going through rehab and physical therapy.</blockquote>\n\nWNBA players are awarded bonuses for certain achievements. Some of the bonuses given by the league (amount is per player), through the 2019 season, include:\nWNBA champion: $10,500; Runner-up: $5,250; Most valuable player: $15,000; All-WNBA First Team member: $10,000; and All-Star Game participant: $2,500.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://womensbasketballonline.com/wnba/rosters/salary.html|title=womensbasketballonline.com|access-date=2013-03-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130801060900/http://womensbasketballonline.com/wnba/rosters/salary.html|archive-date=2013-08-01|url-status=dead}}</ref> These amounts are set to increase under the 2020 CBA.\n\n===Merchandise===\nThe following shows the top jersey sales during the [[2019 WNBA season|2019 regular season]].<ref name=\"2019 jerseys\">{{cite press release|url=https://www.wnba.com/news/elena-delle-donne-leads-wnbas-most-popular-jerseys-list-for-third-consecutive-season/ |title=Elena Delle Donne Leads WNBA\u2019S Most Popular Jerseys List For Third Consecutive Season |publisher=WNBA |date=September 12, 2019 |accessdate=September 14, 2019}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width: 100%\"\n|-\n!colspan=11|Jersey Sales\n|- align=center\n!width=7%|Rank\n|width=9.3%| '''1''' ||width=9.3%| '''2''' ||width=9.3%| '''3''' ||width=9.3%| '''4''' ||width=9.3%| '''5''' ||width=9.3%| '''6''' ||width=9.3%| '''7''' ||width=9.3%| '''8''' ||width=9.3%| '''9''' ||width=9.3%| '''10'''\n|-\n!width=7%|Player\n| [[Elena Delle Donne]] || [[A'ja Wilson]] || [[Candace Parker]] || [[Diana Taurasi]] || [[Sue Bird]] || [[Liz Cambage]] || [[Kelsey Plum]] || [[Arike Ogunbowale]] || [[Breanna Stewart]] || [[Kayla McBride]]\n|-\n!width=7%|Team\n| [[Washington Mystics|Mystics]] || [[Las Vegas Aces|Aces]] || [[Los Angeles Sparks|Sparks]] || [[Phoenix Mercury|Mercury]] || [[Seattle Storm|Storm]] || [[Las Vegas Aces|Aces]] || [[Las Vegas Aces|Aces]] || [[Dallas Wings|Wings]] || [[Seattle Storm|Storm]] || [[Las Vegas Aces|Aces]]\n|}\n\nThe following shows the top teams in merchandise sales during the [[2019 WNBA season|2019 regular season]].<ref name=\"2019 jerseys\"/>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width: 100%\"\n|-\n!colspan=11|Team Sales\n|- align=center\n!width=7%|Rank\n|width=9.3%| '''1''' ||width=9.3%| '''2''' ||width=9.3%| '''3''' ||width=9.3%| '''4''' ||width=9.3%| '''5''' \n|-\n!width=7%|Team\n| [[Las Vegas Aces]] || [[Minnesota Lynx]] || [[Seattle Storm]] || [[New York Liberty]] || [[Washington Mystics]] \n|}\n\n===WNBA Presidents / Commissioners===\n* [[Val Ackerman]], 1996\u20132005\n* [[Donna Orender]], 2005\u20132010\n* [[Chris Granger (WNBA)|Chris Granger]], 2011 <small>(interim)</small>\n* [[Laurel J. Richie]], 2011\u20132015\n* [[Lisa Borders]], 2015\u20132018<ref name=LBStepDown>{{cite web | title=WNBA President Lisa Borders Steps Down to Become First-Ever President and CEO of Time\u2019s Up | url=https://www.wnba.com/news/wnba-president-lisa-borders-steps-down-president-ceo-times-up/ | accessdate=December 22, 2018  | date=October 2, 2018 | publisher=WNBA}}</ref>\n* [[Mark Tatum]], 2018\u20132019 <small>(interim)</small>\n* [[Cathy Engelbert]], 2019\u2013present<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espn.com/wnba/story/_/id/26754371/wnba-tabs-ceo-engelbert-1st-commissioner |title=WNBA tabs CEO Engelbert as 1st commissioner |first=Mechelle |last=Voepel |website=ESPN.com |date=May 15, 2019 |accessdate=May 15, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Attendance==\nIn 2012, the average attendance per game dropped from 7,955 to 7,457 (-6.3%). Attendance per game stayed consistent at around 7,520 per game. In 2015, the WNBA's attendance per game decreased by 3.4 percent to 7,318. This was a record low for the WNBA since it was created in 1997. Many teams have experienced drops in their attendance; (San Antonio Stars: -37.4%, Washington Mystics: -7.9%, Tulsa Shock: -7.2%)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sportsbusinessdaily.com/Journal/Issues/2015/09/21/Leagues-and-Governing-Bodies/WNBA.aspx|title=With 20th season ahead, league sees attendance, ratings drop|website=www.sportsbusinessdaily.com|access-date=2016-10-02}}</ref> these losses have caused the attendance of the WNBA to drop.\n\nPresident Laurel Richie stated that after the 2015 season ends, they will create an expansion committee and begin evaluating if and how the WNBA should go about expanding their reach.\n\nThe 2018 and 2019 seasons each set the lowest average attendance in WNBA history (6,769 and 6,535). However, about half of the decline in attendance from 2017 to 2018 was due to the New York Liberty moving from 19,812-seat [[Madison Square Garden]] to the 5,000-seat [[Westchester County Center]]. While the Liberty had averaged over 9,000 fans in 2017, [[James L. Dolan|James Dolan]], then the team's owner, noted that roughly half of the team's attendance in that season came from complimentary tickets.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.msureporter.com/2019/01/31/wnba-dip-in-attendance-lowest-in-league-history|title=WNBA: Dip in attendance lowest in league history|website=MSU Reporter|access-date=2019-01-31}}</ref> Similarly in 2019, the Washington Mystics moved from the 20,356-seat [[Capital One Arena]] to the 4,111-seat [[St. Elizabeths East Entertainment and Sports Arena]]. The Las Vegas Aces and New York Liberty each saw double-digit percentage losses in 2019, but half of the league's teams saw attendance increases in that season, and the number of sellouts was the same in both seasons (41).<ref name=\"SBD 2019\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sportsbusinessdaily.com/Daily/Issues/2019/09/10/Research-and-Ratings/WNBA-Turnstile-Tracker.aspx |title=WNBA Turnstile Tracker: Attendance Down At End Of Regular Season |first1=Andrew |last1=Levin |first2=David |last2=Broughton |work=Sports Business Daily |date=September 10, 2019 |access-date=October 18, 2019}}</ref>\n\n{{hidden begin|expanded=y|titlestyle=background:#ffe6bd|border=1px #aaa solid|ta1=center|title=Attendance}}\n{{hidden begin|border=1px #aaa solid|ta1=center|title=1990s}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; margin-left:auto; margin-right:auto\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"|Year\n! colspan=\"12\"|Team\n! colspan=\"2\"|League\n|-\n! [[Charlotte Sting|CHA]]\n! [[Cleveland Rockers|CLE]]\n! [[Detroit Shock|DET]]\n! [[Houston Comets|HOU]]\n! [[Los Angeles Sparks|LA]]\n! [[Minnesota Lynx|MIN]]\n! [[New York Liberty|NY]]\n! [[Orlando Miracle|ORL]]\n! [[Phoenix Mercury|PHX]]\n! [[Sacramento Monarchs|SAC]]\n! [[Utah Starzz|UTA]]\n! [[Washington Mystics|WAS]]\n! Regular season\n! Post{{shy}}season\n|-\n|'''[[1997 WNBA season|1997]]'''\n|8,307\n|7,971\n|\n|9,814\n|8,937\n|\n|13,270\n|\n|13,703\n|7,858\n|7,611\n|\n|9,684\n|14,849\n|-\n|'''[[1998 WNBA season|1998]]'''\n|8,561\n|10,350\n|10,229\n|12,602\n|7,653\n|\n|14,935\n|\n|13,764\n|6,578\n|8,104\n|15,910\n|10,869\n|11,964\n|-\n|'''[[1999 WNBA season|1999]]'''\n|7,080\n|9,350\n|8,485\n|11,906\n|7,625\n|10,494\n|14,047\n|9,801\n|12,219\n|8,626\n|7,544\n|15,306\n|10,207\n|12,647\n|}\n{{hidden end}}\n{{hidden begin|border=1px #aaa solid|ta1=center|title=2000s}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; margin-left:auto; margin-right:auto\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"|Year\n! colspan=\"20\"|Team\n! colspan=\"2\"|League\n|-\n! [[Atlanta Dream|ATL]]\n! [[Charlotte Sting|CHA]]\n! [[Chicago Sky|CHI]]\n! [[Cleveland Rockers|CLE]]\n! [[Connecticut Sun|CON]]\n! [[Detroit Shock|DET]]\n! [[Houston Comets|HOU]]\n! [[Indiana Fever|IND]]\n! [[Los Angeles Sparks|LA]]\n! [[Miami Sol|MIA]]\n! [[Minnesota Lynx|MIN]]\n![[New York Liberty|NY]]\n![[Orlando Miracle|ORL]]\n![[Phoenix Mercury|PHX]]\n! [[Portland Fire|POR]]\n![[Sacramento Monarchs|SAC]]\n![[San Antonio Silver Stars|SA]]\n![[Seattle Storm|SEA]]\n![[Utah Starzz|UTA]]\n! [[Washington Mystics|WAS]]\n! Regular season\n! Post{{shy}}season\n|-\n|'''[[2000 WNBA season|2000]]'''\n|\n|5,685\n|\n|8,596\n|\n|6,716\n|12,255\n|12,267\n|6,563\n|7,983\n|7,290\n|14,498\n|7,363\n|10,130\n|