s|2004]]'''\n| [[2004 Seattle Storm season|Seattle Storm]]\n| [[Anne Donovan]]\n| [[Connecticut Sun]]\n| [[Mike Thibault]]\n| [[Betty Lennox]]\n|-\n| '''[[2005 WNBA Finals|2005]]'''\n| {{Nowrap|[[2005 Sacramento Monarchs season|Sacramento Monarchs]]}}\n| [[John Whisenant]]\n| [[Connecticut Sun]]\n| [[Mike Thibault]]\n| rowspan=5|Best-of-five\n| 3\u20131\n| [[Yolanda Griffith]]\n|-\n| '''[[2006 WNBA Finals|2006]]'''\n| [[2006 Detroit Shock season|Detroit Shock]]\n| [[Bill Laimbeer]]\n| [[Sacramento Monarchs]]\n| [[John Whisenant]]\n| rowspan=2|3\u20132\n| [[Deanna Nolan]]\n|-\n| '''[[2007 WNBA Finals|2007]]'''\n| [[2007 Phoenix Mercury season|Phoenix Mercury]]\n| [[Paul Westhead]]\n| [[Detroit Shock]]\n| [[Bill Laimbeer]]\n| [[Cappie Pondexter]]\n|-\n| '''[[2008 WNBA Finals|2008]]'''\n| [[2008 Detroit Shock season|Detroit Shock]]\n| [[Bill Laimbeer]]\n| {{Nowrap|[[San Antonio Silver Stars]]}}\n| [[Dan Hughes (basketball coach)|Dan Hughes]]\n| 3\u20130\n| [[Katie Smith]]\n|-\n| '''[[2009 WNBA Finals|2009]]'''\n| [[2009 Phoenix Mercury season|Phoenix Mercury]]\n| [[Corey Gaines]]\n| [[Indiana Fever]]\n| [[Lin Dunn]]\n| 3\u20132\n| [[Diana Taurasi]]\n|}\n{{hidden end}}\n{{hidden begin|expanded=y|border=1px #aaa solid|ta1=center|title=2010s}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:4%;\" rowspan=\"2\"| Season\n! style=\"width:16%;\" colspan=\"2\"| Champion\n! style=\"width:16%;\" colspan=\"2\"| Runner-Up\n! style=\"width:5%;\" rowspan=\"2\"| Format\n! style=\"width:3%;\" rowspan=\"2\"| Result\n! style=\"width:8%;\" rowspan=\"2\"| Finals MVP\n|-\n! style=\"width:8%;\"|Team\n! style=\"width:8%;\"|Coach\n! style=\"width:8%;\"|Team\n! style=\"width:8%;\"|Coach\n|-\n| '''[[2010 WNBA Finals|2010]]'''\n| [[2010 Seattle Storm season|Seattle Storm]]\n| [[Brian Agler]]\n| rowspan=2|[[Atlanta Dream]]\n| rowspan=2|[[Marynell Meadors]]\n| rowspan=10|Best-of-five\n| rowspan=2|3\u20130\n| [[Lauren Jackson]]\n|-\n| '''[[2011 WNBA Finals|2011]]'''\n| [[2011 Minnesota Lynx season|Minnesota Lynx]]\n| [[Cheryl Reeve]]\n| [[Seimone Augustus]]\n|-\n| '''[[2012 WNBA Finals|2012]]'''\n| [[2012 Indiana Fever season|Indiana Fever]]\n| [[Lin Dunn]]\n| [[Minnesota Lynx]]\n| [[Cheryl Reeve]]\n| 3\u20131\n| [[Tamika Catchings]]\n|-\n| '''[[2013 WNBA Finals|2013]]'''\n| [[2013 Minnesota Lynx season|Minnesota Lynx]]\n| [[Cheryl Reeve]]\n| [[Atlanta Dream]]\n| [[Fred Williams (basketball, born 1957)|Fred Williams]]\n| rowspan=2|3\u20130\n| [[Maya Moore]]\n|-\n| '''[[2014 WNBA Finals|2014]]'''\n| [[2014 Phoenix Mercury season|Phoenix Mercury]]\n| [[Sandy Brondello]]\n| [[Chicago Sky]]\n| [[Pokey Chatman]]\n| [[Diana Taurasi]]\n|-\n| '''[[2015 WNBA Finals|2015]]'''\n| [[2015 Minnesota Lynx season|Minnesota Lynx]]\n| [[Cheryl Reeve]]\n| [[Indiana Fever]]\n| [[Stephanie White]]\n| rowspan=3|3\u20132\n| [[Sylvia Fowles]]\n|-\n| '''[[2016 WNBA Finals|2016]]'''\n|[[Los Angeles Sparks]]\n|[[Brian Agler]]\n|[[Minnesota Lynx]]\n|[[Cheryl Reeve]]\n|[[Candace Parker]]\n|-\n| '''[[2017 WNBA Finals|2017]]'''\n|[[Minnesota Lynx]]\n|[[Cheryl Reeve]]\n|[[Los Angeles Sparks]]\n|[[Brian Agler]]\n|[[Sylvia Fowles]]\n|-\n| '''[[2018 WNBA Finals|2018]]'''\n| [[2018 Seattle Storm season|Seattle Storm]]\n| [[Dan Hughes (basketball)|Dan Hughes]]\n| [[Washington Mystics]]\n| [[Mike Thibault]]\n| 3\u20130\n| [[Breanna Stewart]]\n|-\n| '''[[2019 WNBA Finals|2019]]'''\n| [[Washington Mystics]]\n| [[Mike Thibault]]\n| [[Connecticut Sun]]\n| [[Curt Miller]]\n| 3\u20132\n| [[Emma Meesseman]]\n|} \n{{hidden end}}\n{{hidden end}}\n\n==League championships==\nThe [[Houston Comets]] and [[Minnesota Lynx]] hold the distinction of having won the most championships with 4 titles each. The Comets folded in 2008. The Lynx have the most appearances in the championship with 6, all occurring in the 7 years from 2011-2017.\n''Teams in red have folded and can no longer reach the WNBA Finals.''\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n!Teams!!|Win!!|Loss!!|Total!!|Year(s) won!!|Year(s) lost\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left\"|[[Minnesota Lynx]]||4||2||6||style=\"text-align:left\"|[[2011 WNBA Finals|2011]], [[2013 WNBA Finals|2013]], [[2015 WNBA Finals|2015]], [[2017 WNBA Finals|2017]]||style=\"text-align:left\"|[[2012 WNBA Finals|2012]], [[2016 WNBA Finals|2016]]\n|-style=\"background: #ffdfdf;\"\n|style=\"text-align:left\"|[[Houston Comets]] <small>(folded in 2008)</small>||4||0||4||style=\"text-align:left\"|[[1997 WNBA Finals|1997]], [[1998 WNBA Finals|1998]], [[1999 WNBA Finals|1999]], [[2000 WNBA Finals|2000]]||-\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left\"|[[Los Angeles Sparks]]||3||2||5||style=\"text-align:left\"|[[2001 WNBA Finals|2001]], [[2002 WNBA Finals|2002]], [[2016 WNBA Finals|2016]]||style=\"text-align:left\"|[[2003 WNBA Finals|2003]], [[2017 WNBA Finals|2017]]\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left\"|[[Phoenix Mercury]]||3||1||4||style=\"text-align:left\"|[[2007 WNBA Finals|2007]], [[2009 WNBA Finals|2009]], [[2014 WNBA Finals|2014]]||style=\"text-align:left\"|[[1998 WNBA Finals|1998]]\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left\"|[[Detroit Shock]] <small>(now Dallas Wings)</small> ||3||1||4||style=\"text-align:left\"|[[2003 WNBA Finals|2003]], [[2006 WNBA Finals|2006]], [[2008 WNBA Finals|2008]]||style=\"text-align:left\"|[[2007 WNBA Finals|2007]]\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left\"|[[Seattle Storm]]||3||0||3||style=\"text-align:left\"|[[2004 WNBA Finals|2004]], [[2010 WNBA Finals|2010]], [[2018 WNBA Finals|2018]]||-\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left\"|[[Indiana Fever]]||1||2||3||style=\"text-align:left\"|[[2012 WNBA Finals|2012]]||style=\"text-align:left\"|[[2009 WNBA Finals|2009]], [[2015 WNBA Finals|2015]]\n|-style=\"background: #ffdfdf;\"\n|style=\"text-align:left\"|[[Sacramento Monarchs]] <small>(folded in 2009)</small>||1||1||2||style=\"text-align:left\"|[[2005 WNBA Finals|2005]]||style=\"text-align:left\"|[[2006 WNBA Finals|2006]]\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left\"|[[Washington Mystics]]||1||1||2||style=\"text-align:left\"|[[2019 WNBA Finals|2019]]||style=\"text-align:left\"|[[2018 WNBA Finals|2018]]\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left\"|[[New York Liberty]]||0||4||4||-||style=\"text-align:left\"|[[1997 WNBA Finals|1997]], [[1999 WNBA Finals|1999]], [[2000 WNBA Finals|2000]], [[2002 WNBA Finals|2002]]\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left\"|[[Atlanta Dream]]||0||3||3||-||style=\"text-align:left\"|[[2010 WNBA Finals|2010]], [[2011 WNBA Finals|2011]], [[2013 WNBA Finals|2013]]\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left\"|[[Connecticut Sun]]||0||3||3||-||style=\"text-align:left\"|[[2004 WNBA Finals|2004]], [[2005 WNBA Finals|2005]], [[2019 WNBA Finals|2019]]\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left\"|[[Chicago Sky]]||0||1||1||-||style=\"text-align:left\"|[[2014 WNBA Finals|2014]]\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left\"|[[San Antonio Stars]] <small>(now Las Vegas Aces)</small> ||0||1||1||-||style=\"text-align:left\"|[[2008 WNBA Finals|2008]]\n|-style=\"background: #ffdfdf;\"\n|style=\"text-align:left\"|[[Charlotte Sting]] <small>(folded in 2006)</small>||0||1||1||-||style=\"text-align:left\"|[[2001 WNBA Finals|2001]]\n|}\n\nFormer teams that have no [[WNBA Finals]] appearances: \n*[[Cleveland Rockers]] (1997\u20132003)\n*[[Miami Sol]] (2000\u20132002) \n*[[Portland Fire]] (2000\u20132002)\n\n==Players and coaches==\n{{Main|List of Women's National Basketball Association players|List of Women's National Basketball Association head coaches}}\n{{see also|List of foreign WNBA players}}\n[[File:WNBA Sue Bird cropped.jpg|right|thumb|200px|[[Sue Bird]], a member of the [[WNBA's All-Decade Team|All-Decade]], [[WNBA's Top 15 Team|Top 15]], and [[WNBA Top 20@20|Top 20]] teams]]\nIn 2011, a decade and a half after the launch of the WNBA, only two players remained from the league's [[1997 WNBA season|inaugural season in 1997]]: [[Sheryl Swoopes]] and [[Tina Thompson]]. [[Lisa Leslie]] was the longest-tenured player from the 1997 draft class; she spent her entire career (1997\u20132009) with the [[Los Angeles Sparks]]. [[Sue Bird]] holds both of the league's most significant longevity records\u2014number of seasons in the league (16) and games played (508).\n\nThe members of the [[WNBA's All-Decade Team]] were chosen in 2006 on the occasion of the tenth anniversary of the WNBA from amongst 30 nominees compiled by fans, media, coach, and player voting. The team was to comprise the 10 best and most influential players of the first decade of the WNBA, with consideration also given to sportsmanship, community service, leadership, and contribution to the growth of women's basketball.\n\nPlayers for the [[WNBA's Top 15 Team]] were chosen in 2011 on the anniversary of the league's fifteenth season from amongst 30 nominees compiled similarly to that of the All-Decade Team process. This process was repeated for the league's 20th anniversary season in 2016 with the selection of the [[WNBA Top 20@20]].\n\nOver [[WNBA Career Scoring|30 players]] have scored at least 3,000 points in their WNBA careers. Only nine WNBA players have reached the 6,000 point milestone: Diana Taurasi, Tina Thompson, Tamika Catchings, Cappie Pondexter, Katie Smith, Lisa Leslie, Sue Bird, Candice Dupree, and Lauren Jackson. The scoring average leader is [[Cynthia Cooper-Dyke|Cynthia Cooper]], who averaged 21.0 points per game<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/wnba/leaders/pts_per_g_career.html |title=WNBA Career Leaders and Records for Points Per Game |website=Basketball-Reference.com |accessdate=August 28, 2018}}</ref> in five seasons with the Houston Comets (1997\u20132000, 2003).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/wnba/players/c/coopecy01w.html |title=Cynthia Cooper WNBA Stats |website=Basketball-Reference.com |accessdate=August 29, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2007, [[Paul Westhead]] of the [[Phoenix Mercury]] became the first person to earn both NBA and WNBA championship rings as a coach.\n\nIn 2008, 50-year-old [[Nancy Lieberman]] became the oldest player to play in a WNBA game. She signed a seven-day contract with the [[Detroit Shock]] and played one game, tallying [https://web.archive.org/web/20080912150859/http://www.wnba.com/games/20080724/DETHOU/boxscore.html two assists and two turnovers] in nine minutes of action. By playing in the one game Lieberman broke a record that she had set in 1997 when she was the league's oldest player at 39.\n\nSue Bird, who has played for the Seattle Storm since 2002, holds the record for career assists<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/wnba/leaders/ast_career.html |title=WNBA Career Leaders and Records for Assists |website=Basketball-Reference.com |accessdate=August 28, 2018}}</ref> with 2,831 in 508 regular-season games.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/wnba/players/b/birdsu01w.html |title=Sue Bird WNBA Stats |website=Basketball-Reference.com |accessdate=August 28, 2018}}</ref> The record for most assists per game is currently held by [[Courtney Vandersloot]], an American who also holds a Hungarian passport and represents [[Hungary women's national basketball team|that country]] internationally. She has averaged 6.17 assists per game during her career with the Chicago Sky (2011\u2013present).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/wnba/leaders/ast_per_g_career.html |title=WNBA Career Leaders and Records for Assists Per Game |website=Basketball-Reference.com |accessdate=September 15, 2019}}</ref> Vandersloot also has the top three seasons in assists per game, with 8.1 in 2017, 8.6 in 2018, and 9.1 in 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/wnba/leaders/ast_per_g_season.html |title=WNBA Single Season Leaders and Records for Assists Per Game |website=Basketball-Reference.com |accessdate=September 15, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Milestones ===\n{{see also|WNBA records}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin:1em auto;\"\n|-\n|+ WNBA Milestones\n|-\n!Milestone\n!Player\n!Team\n!Date\n!Information\n|-\n| First player signed\n| [[Sheryl Swoopes]]\n| [[Houston Comets]]\n| October 23, 1996\n| Signed by the WNBA and assigned to [[Houston Comets|Houston]].\n|-\n| First points scored\n| [[Penny Toler]]\n| [[Los Angeles Sparks]]\n| June 21, 1997\n| Scored the first points on a baseline jump-shot.\n|-\n| First triple-double\n| [[Sheryl Swoopes]]\n| [[Houston Comets]]\n| July 27, 1998\n| 14 points, 15 rebounds, 10 assists\n|-\n| First goaltending call\n| [[Sylvia Fowles]]\n| [[Chicago Sky]]\n| June 3, 2008\n| Trying to block a layup by [[Lisa Leslie]].\n|-\n| First slam dunk\n| [[Lisa Leslie]]\n| [[Los Angeles Sparks]]\n| July 30, 2002\n| Dunked on a fast break against [[Miami Sol|Miami]]\n|-\n| First [[50\u201340\u201390 club|50\u201340\u201390 season]]\n| [[Elena Delle Donne]]\n| [[Washington Mystics]]\n| 2019\n| 51.5% FG, 43.0% 3FG, 97.4% FT<ref name=\"EDD 50\u201340\u201390\"/>\n|-\n| Most career points\n| [[Diana Taurasi]]\n| [[Phoenix Mercury]]\n| 2004\u20132014, 2016\u2013present\n| 8,549 points\n|-\n| Most career rebounds\n| [[Rebekkah Brunson]]\n| [[Sacramento Monarchs]] / [[Minnesota Lynx]]\n| 2004\u20132019\n| 3,356 rebounds\n|-\n| Most career assists\n| [[Sue Bird]]\n| [[Seattle Storm]]\n| 2002\u20132012, 2014\u2013present\n| 2,831 assists\n|-\n| Most 3-pointers\n| [[Diana Taurasi]]\n| [[Phoenix Mercury]]\n| 2004\u20132014, 2016\u2013present\n| 1,102 3-pointers\n|-\n| Most points in a game\n| [[Liz Cambage]]\n| [[Dallas Wings]]\n| July 17, 2018\n| 53 points\n|-\n| Most rebounds in a game\n| [[Chamique Holdsclaw]]\n| [[Washington Mystics]]\n| May 23, 2003\n| 24 rebounds\n|-\n| Most assists in a game\n| [[Ticha Penicheiro]]\n| [[Sacramento Monarchs]]\n| July 29, 1998 &<br />August 3, 2002\n| 16 assists\n|-\n| Most career wins for a coach\n| [[Mike Thibault]]\n| [[Connecticut Sun]] / [[Washington Mystics]]<ref>http://www.wnba.com/mystics/news/mike_thibault_070613.html</ref>\n| 2003\u2013present\n| 336 wins\n|-\n| Most team points in one game\n| -\n| [[Phoenix Mercury]]\n| July 24, 2010\n| 127 points in double overtime against [[Minnesota Lynx|Minnesota]]\n|-\n| Most team points in a regulation game\n| -\n| [[Phoenix Mercury]]\n| July 22, 2010\n| 123 points against [[Tulsa Shock|Tulsa]]\n|-\n| Largest margin of victory\n| -\n| [[Seattle Storm]]\n| August 7, 2010\n| 46-point win (111\u201365) over [[Tulsa Shock|Tulsa]]\n|-\n| Largest attendance for one game\n| -\n| [[Detroit Shock]]\n| September 16, 2007\n| 22,076 in game 5 of [[2007 WNBA Finals|2007 Finals]]\n|}\n\n===Awards===\nAround the beginning of September (or late August in Olympic and [[FIBA Women's Basketball World Cup|FIBA World Cup]] years), the regular season ends. It is during this time that voting begins for individual awards. The [[WNBA Sixth Woman of the Year Award|Sixth Woman of the Year Award]] is given to the best player coming off the bench (must have more games coming off the bench than actual games started).<ref name=WNBA6th>{{cite web|url=http://www.wnba.com/news/awards07_sixth.html|title=Detroit's Plenette Pierson Named 2007 WNBA Sixth Woman of the Year|publisher=WNBA}}</ref> The [[WNBA Rookie of the Year Award|Rookie of the Year Award]] is awarded to the most outstanding first-year player. The [[WNBA Most Improved Player Award|Most Improved Player Award]] is awarded to the player who is deemed to have shown the most improvement from the previous season. The [[WNBA Defensive Player of the Year Award|Defensive Player of the Year Award]] is awarded to the league's best defender. The [[Kim Perrot Sportsmanship Award]] is awarded to the player who shows outstanding sportsmanship on and off the court. The [[WNBA Coach of the Year Award|Coach of the Year Award]] is awarded to the coach that has made the most positive difference to a team. The [[WNBA Most Valuable Player Award|Most Valuable Player Award]] is given to the player deemed the most valuable for her team that season. The newest WNBA award is the [[WNBA Basketball Executive of the Year Award|Basketball Executive of the Year Award]], first presented in 2017 to the team executive most instrumental in his or her team's success in that season.\n\nAlso named are the [[All-WNBA Teams]], the [[WNBA All-Defensive Team|All-Defensive Teams]], and the [[WNBA All-Rookie Team|All-Rookie Team]]; each consists of five players. There are two All-WNBA teams, consisting of the top players at each position, with the first-team status being the most desirable. There are two All-Defensive teams, consisting of the top defenders at each position. There is one All-Rookie team, consisting of the top first-year players regardless of position.\n\n====Most recent award winners====\nWinners are from the most recent season unless otherwise indicated.\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width: 85%; margin:1em auto;\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"width:155px;\"|Award\n!width=125|Winner\n!width=100|Position\n!width=135|Team\n!width=115|Votes/Statistic{{efn|\"Votes\" are listed as first-place votes, although the winners for all WNBA awards apart from the statistically based Peak Performer Awards are determined by points earned rather than first-place votes.}}\n|-\n|colspan=2| '''[[WNBA Most Valuable Player Award|Most Valuable Player Award]]'''\n| [[Elena Delle Donne]]\n| Guard\u2013forward\n| [[Washington Mystics]]\n| 41 out of 43\n|-\n|colspan=2| '''[[WNBA Finals MVP Award|Finals MVP Award]]'''\n| [[Emma Meesseman]]\n| Center\n| [[Washington Mystics]]\n| \n|-\n|colspan=2| '''[[WNBA Rookie of the Year Award|Rookie of the Year Award]]'''\n| [[Napheesa Collier]]\n| Forward\n| [[Minnesota Lynx]]\n| 29 out of 43\n|-\n|colspan=2| '''[[WNBA Most Improved Player Award|Most Improved Player Award]]'''\n| [[Leilani Mitchell]]\n| Guard\n| [[Phoenix Mercury]]\n| 27 out of 43\n|-\n|colspan=2| '''[[WNBA Defensive Player of the Year Award|Defensive Player of the Year Award]]'''\n| [[Natasha Howard (basketball)|Natasha Howard]]\n| Forward\n| [[Seattle Storm]]\n| 33 out of 43\n|-\n|colspan=2| '''[[WNBA Sixth Woman of the Year Award|Sixth Woman of the Year Award]]'''\n| [[Dearica Hamby]] \n| Forward\n| [[Las Vegas Aces]]\n| 41 out of 43\n|-\n|colspan=2| '''[[Kim Perrot Sportsmanship Award]]'''\n| [[Nneka Ogwumike]]\n| Forward\n| [[Los Angeles Sparks]]\n| 7 out of 43\n|-\n|colspan=2| '''[[WNBA Peak Performers|Peak Performer: Points]]'''\n| [[Brittney Griner]]\n| Center\n| [[Phoenix Mercury]]\n| 20.7 PPG\n|-\n|colspan=2| '''[[WNBA Peak Performers|Peak Performer: Rebounds]]'''\n| [[Jonquel Jones]]\n| Center\n| [[Connecticut Sun]]\n| 9.7 RPG\n|-\n|colspan=2| '''[[WNBA Peak Performers|Peak Performer: Assists]]'''\n| [[Courtney Vandersloot]]\n| Guard\n| [[Chicago Sky]]\n| 9.1 APG{{efn|WNBA record.<ref name=\"EDD 50\u201340\u201390\">{{cite news|url=https://www.espn.com/wnba/story/_/id/27573501/delle-donne-first-wnba-join-50-40-90-club |title=Delle Donne first in WNBA to join 50-40-90 club |website=ESPN.com |date=September 8, 2019 |accessdate=September 9, 2019}}</ref>}}\n|-\n|colspan=2| '''[[WNBA Coach of the Year Award|Coach of the Year Award]]'''\n| [[James Wade (basketball)|James Wade]]\n| Coach\n| [[Chicago Sky]]\n| 27 out of 43\n|-\n|colspan=2| '''[[WNBA Basketball Executive of the Year Award|Basketball Executive of the Year Award]]'''\n| [[Cheryl Reeve]]\n| General manager\n| [[Minnesota Lynx]]\n| 4 out of 11\n|}\n\n;Notes\n{{notelist|group=award}}\n\n====Retired numbers====\n[[File: Lauren Jackson 2a.JPG|thumb|right|160px|Lauren Jackson, one of the most notable players in WNBA history. Number 15 was retired by Seattle Storm in her honour.]]\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! width=40px|No.\n! width=150px|Team\n! width=150px|Player\n! width=40px|Pos.\n! width=100px|Tenure{{efn|group=note|Reflects tenure with the team that retired the player's number; not necessarily identical to the player's WNBA tenure.}}\n! width=40px|Ref.\n|-\n| '''9''' || rowspan=2|[[Los Angeles Sparks]] || {{sortname|Lisa|Leslie}} || [[Center (basketball)|C]] || 1997\u20132009 || <ref>[http://www.espn.com/news/story?id=5450577 Sparks to retire Lisa Leslie's jersey] on ESPN, 