{"title_page": "Woolwich, Ontario", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement\n| name                            = Woolwich\n| official_name                   = Township of WoolWittch\n| settlement_type                 = [[List of township municipalities in Ontario|Township]] ([[List of municipalities in Ontario#Lower-tier municipalities|lower-tier]])\n| other_name                      = \n| native_name                     = <!-- for cities whose native name is not in English -->\n| nickname                        = \n| motto                           = \n| image_skyline                   = Aerial_Woolwich.jpg\n| image_caption                   = \n| image_flag                      = \n| flag_size                       = \n| image_seal                      = \n| seal_size                       = \n| image_shield                    = \n| shield_size                     = \n| image_blank_emblem              = \n| blank_emblem_size               = \n| image_map                       = \n| mapsize                         = \n| map_caption                     = \n| pushpin_map                     = Canada Southern Ontario\n| pushpin_label_position          = \n| pushpin_mapsize                 = 200\n| coordinates                     = {{coord|43|34|N|80|29|W|region:CA-ON|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type                = [[Countries of the world|Country]]\n| subdivision_name                = {{CAN}}\n| subdivision_type1               = [[Provinces and territories of Canada|Province]]\n| subdivision_name1               = {{ON}}\n| subdivision_type2               = [[Census divisions of Ontario|Regional municipality]]\n| subdivision_name2               = [[Regional Municipality of Waterloo|Waterloo]]\n| subdivision_type3               = \n| subdivision_name3               = \n| subdivision_type4               = \n| subdivision_name4               = \n| government_type                 = Township\n| leader_title                    = Mayor\n| leader_name                     = Sandy Shantz <ref name=2018elec>{{cite web |url= https://www.woolwich.ca/en/elections/resources/Woolwich-Township-2018-Election---Official-Results.pdf |title= Woolwich Township Official Election Results |publisher= Woolwich Township |accessdate=2018-12-14}}</ref>\n| leader_title1                   = Councillors\n| leader_name1                    = {{Collapsible list\n|title = List\n|frame_style = border:none; padding: 0;\n|list_style = text-align:left;display:none;\n|1= Scott Hahn\n|2= Patrick Merlihan\n|3= Fred Redekop\n|4= Murray Martin\n|5= Lary Shantz\n}}\n| leader_title2                   = Governing Body\n| leader_name2                    = Woolwich Township Council\n| leader_title3                   = [[House of Commons of Canada|MP]]\n| leader_name3                    = [[Harold Albrecht]] ([[Conservative Party of Canada|CPC]])\n| leader_title4                   = [[Legislative Assembly of Ontario|MPP]]\n| leader_name4                    = [[Mike Harris Jr. (politician)|Mike Harris Jr.]] ([[Ontario Progressive Conservative Party|PC]])\n| established_title               = Settled\n| established_date                = 1798\n| established_title2              = Incorporated\n| established_date2               = \n| established_title3              = \n| established_date3               = \n| area_magnitude                  = \n| area_footnotes                  = <ref name=\"cp2011\">{{cite web |url=http://www12.statcan.ca/census-recensement/2011/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CSD&Code1=3530035&Geo2=CD&Code2=3530&Data=Count&SearchText=Woolwich&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&Custom=&TABID=1 |title=Woolwich, Ontario (Code 3530035) census profile |publisher=Statistics Canada |work=[[Canada 2011 Census|2011 Census of Population]] |accessdate=2012-08-17}}</ref>\n| area_total_km2                  = \n| area_land_km2                   = 326.15\n| area_water_km2                  = \n| area_water_percent              = \n| population_as_of                = 2016\n| population_footnotes            = <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/dp-pd/prof/details/Page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CSD&Code1=3530035&Geo2=PR&Code2=47&Data=Count&SearchText=Waterloo&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All |title=Census Profile, 2016 Census: Woolwich, Township|publisher=Statistics Canada|accessdate=May 22, 2019}}</ref>\n| population_note                 = \n| population_total                = 25,006\n| population_density_km2          = 76.7\n| timezone                        = [[North American Eastern Time Zone|EST]]\n| utc_offset                      = -5\n| timezone_DST                    = [[Eastern Daylight Time|EDT]]\n| utc_offset_DST                  = -4\n| elevation_footnotes             = <!--for references: use <ref> </ref> tags-->\n| elevation_m                     = \n| postal_code_type                = Postal code span\n| postal_code                     = \n| area_code                       = [[Area codes 519 and 226|519 and 226]]\n| website                         = [http://www.woolwich.ca/ www.woolwich.ca]\n| footnotes                       = \n}}\n\n[[File:Woolwich Township, Ontario.PNG|thumb|Woolwich within Waterloo Region]]\nThe '''Township of Woolwich''' is a [[rural]] [[township (Canada)|township]] in [[Southwestern Ontario]], Canada, considered as a municipality. The Township is located in the northeast part of Waterloo Region and is made up of 10 small communities, with [[Elmira, Ontario]] the largest and [[St. Jacobs, Ontario]] the second largest. The population at the time of the 2016 Census was 25,006, up slightly from the 2011 population of 23,145. Waterloo Region is still home to the largest population of [[Old Order Mennonite|Old Order Mennonites]] in Canada, particularly in the areas around St Jacobs and Elmira.<ref name=\"OOM\">{{cite web |url=https://canadaalive.wordpress.com/2014/03/31/old-order-mennonites/ |title=Old Order Mennonites |website=Canada Alive!|date=March 31, 2014 |accessdate=May 22, 2019}}</ref> They are often seen on the local roads using their traditional horse and buggy transportation; many also use horses to pull the implements in their farm fields.<ref name=\"OOM\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://gameo.org/index.php?title=Old_Order_Mennonites |title=Old Order Mennonites |website=Global Anabaptist Mennonite Encyclopedia Online (GAMEO)|accessdate=May 22, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.woolwich.ca/en/discover-us/Tours-and-Self-Guided-Tours.aspx |title=Tours and Self-Guided Tours |publisher=Woolwich Township |accessdate=May 22, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.canadianmennonite.org/stories/old-order-mennonite-groups-ontario-are-growing |title=Old Order Mennonite groups in Ontario are growing |publisher=Canadian Mennonite Magazine |date=December 1, 2015 |first=Barb |last=Draper |accessdate=May 22, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.woolwich.ca/en/living-here/About-Woolwich.aspx |title=About Woolwich |publisher=Woolwich Township |accessdate=May 22, 2019}}</ref>\n\nWoolwich is part of the [[Regional Municipality of Waterloo]] and is located directly to the north and east of the [[Waterloo, Ontario|City of Waterloo]]. It is bounded by the cities of [[Kitchener, Ontario|Kitchener]], [[Waterloo, Ontario|Waterloo]], and [[Cambridge, Ontario|Cambridge]]. The township is a municipality as established by the Regional Municipality of Waterloo Act 1972, which created a regional government structure and established limits of the local municipalities effective January 1, 1973.  Woolwich Township has its own municipal government consisting of five Councillors and a Mayor; the latter also serves on the Waterloo Region Council.<ref name=\"MayorCouncil\">{{cite web |title=Mayor and Council |url=https://www.woolwich.ca/en/township-services/Mayor-and-Council.aspx |publisher=Woolwich Township |accessdate=May 22, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe land which now makes up Woolwich Township, with the Grand River on the East, and the Conestogo River on the West, originally belonged to the Huron Nation followed by the Mohawk Nation. The first settlers arrived in the late 18th century. In 1798, William Wallace was one of the first settlers after he was deeded 86,078 acres (348 km2) of land on the Grand River for a cost of $16,364. Originally Block three of Indian Lands, this area now comprises a large part of Woolwich Township. The parcel of land called \"Woolwich\" was probably named (in 1816) after a town in Kent, England. The early settlers were primarily from England or Ireland until about 1830; they settled to the east of the Grand River. Afterwards, German Mennonite families from Pennsylvania and from Waterloo Township settled west of the river.<ref>{{cite web |title=Woolwich Township |url=https://www.waterlooregionmuseum.ca/en/collections-and-research/woolwich-township.aspx |publisher=Ken Seiling Waterloo Region Museum |accessdate=May 22, 2019}} (section \"History of Woolwich Township\")</ref>\n\nIn 1807, Wallace sold the major portion of his tract to Mennonites from Pennsylvania, trustees for the German Company, many of whom would settle this area.<ref>{{cite book | title = County of Waterloo Gazetteer and General Business Directory, For 1864 | publisher = Mitchell & Co. | year = 1864 | url = http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/obj/001075/f2/e010780571_p2.pdf | pages = 61}}</ref> Wallace sold {{convert|45185|acre|km2|0}} of land to the German Company at $1.00 an acre. Captain Smith, a loyalist from Vermont, settled at the confluence of the Grand and Conestogo Rivers in 1807. Their large log home served as an inn for travelers and he operated a stagecoach for carrying mail from 1835 to 1850. The first church in Woolwich, was built by the Mennonites from Pennsylvania in approximately 1823 at the Three Bridges, now part of Conestogo.<ref name=\"WHSp16\">{{cite book |url=http://www.whs.ca/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/1933_V21.pdf |title=Twenty-first and Twenty-second Annual Reports |publisher=Waterloo Historical Society|page=16|accessdate=May 22, 2019}}</ref>  Woolwich was incorporated as a Township in 1816, and was part of Halton County until 1842 when it became part of Wellington District. In 1852, it became part of the new [[Waterloo County]].<ref>{{cite book |url=http://www.whs.ca/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/1933_V21.pdf |title=Twenty-first and Twenty-second Annual Reports |publisher=Waterloo Historical Society|pages=12\u201315|accessdate=May 22, 2019}}</ref>\n\nStarting in 1821, a part of Woolwich, to the east of the Grand River (Block 3), owned by James Crooks, attracted  dozens of families from England and Scotland. Previously, this area had few settlers, the most notable a Mr. Cox; the creek which enters the Grand River at what is now Winterbourne was named after him. Immigrants from Scotland began settling the Cox Creek area in 1834, led by John Davidson. He opened the first post office in the township, naming it East Woolwich. Captain Henry Lanphier arrived in 1854 and soon built a sawmill and flour mill after damming Cox Creek. Residents agreed with him that the settlement should be renamed [[Winterbourne, Ontario]]. By 1837, the Scots established St. Andrew's Presbyterian in 1837. A Presbyterian church was not built until 1870, made of logs; it was replaced in 1870 by one built of brick, and is currently a private home near the Winterbourne Presbyterian Cemetery. By 1867, Winterbourne  had a population of 160, three churches, a school, a post office, a general store, two mills, two hotels, two blacksmiths, a tailor, shoemaker and a physician.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Mills |first1=Rych |title=Flash from the Past: A Scottish enclave in Woolwich Township |url=https://www.therecord.com/living-story/7607547-flash-from-the-past-a-scottish-enclave-in-woolwich-township/ |accessdate=May 22, 2019 |work=Waterloo Region Record |publisher=Metroland News |date=October 13, 2017}}</ref>\n \nSt. Jacobs, like nearby Conestogo (both in Woolwich), was primarily Germanic and was first settled in 1830.<ref name=\"StJacobs\">{{cite web |title=Woolwich Township |url=https://www.waterlooregionmuseum.ca/en/collections-and-research/woolwich-township.aspx |publisher=Ken Seiling Waterloo Region Museum |accessdate=May 22, 2019}} (section \"St. Jacobs\")</ref> In 1834, Edward Bristow from Sussex, England<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mcburney.ca/mcburney/3252.htm |title=Hannah Streater|publisher=Lloyd McBurney |accessdate=May 22, 2019}}</ref> became one of Elmira's first settlers when he purchased {{convert|53|acre|m2}} of land at this location for 50 cents per acre. He started the first store, tavern and potashery.<ref>{{cite web |title=Elmira Travel Guide |url=http://www.elmira-on.worldweb.com/ |website=Worldweb.com |accessdate=May 23, 2019}}</ref> A community by the name of Bristow's Corners was already in existence in 1839 when a post office was assigned there; it was renamed Elmira in 1853.\n\n[[File:Mennonite carriage (cropped).jpg|thumb|right|Old Order Mennonite buggy still common in Woolwich Township]]\n\nHistorical records suggest that David Musselman founded Conestoga after buying land in 1830. He built a sawmill in 1844 and after damming the Conestoga River, he added a flour mill and a second sawmill. The hamlet formed in this area, known as Musselman's Mills until 1852 when it became Conestoga because many of the settlers had come from the Conestoga River area of Pennsylvania.<ref name=\"WHSp16\"/> Records about the entire township from 1846 indicate that the area was thinly settled although the land was excellent and there were large tracts of hardwood. There were two grist and two saw mills and an Episcopal church. The population count in 1841 indicated 1009 people.<ref>{{cite book |last=Smith |first=Wm. H. |date=1846 |title=Smith's Canadian Gazetteer - Statistical and General Information Respecting all parts of The Upper Province, or Canada West|url=https://archive.org/details/smithscanadianga00smit |location=Toronto |publisher=H. & W. Rowsell |pages=[https://archive.org/details/smithscanadianga00smit/page/223 223]\u2013224}}</ref>\n\nWoolwich Township Council was organized in January 1850 with five councillors, of whom John N. Meyer was named as Reeve; James Dow was appointed as clerk and treasurer.<ref>{{cite book |url=http://www.whs.ca/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/1933_V21.pdf |title=Twenty-first and Twenty-second Annual Reports |publisher=Waterloo Historical Society|page=14|accessdate=May 22, 2019}}</ref> A significant influx to the St. Jacobs area started afterwards, primarily consisting of additional Mennonites from Pennsylvania. Farmer and pioneer industrialist Jacob C. Snider, of Swiss German descent, was the most important settler at the time and the community was named after him: Jakobstettel (Jacob's Village). He built a dam to power several mills and then built a sawmill, woolen mill and flour mill by 1852. This helped to attract others to the small community.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Village of St. Jacobs: A Glimpse into Ontario's Mennonite Heritage|url=http://magiccarpetjournals.com/St_Jacobs.htm|publisher=Magic Carpet Journal}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.stjacobs.com/userContent/documents/Our%20Stories/SELFGUIDEDHISTORICWALKINGTOURWeb_000.pdf |title=St. Jacobs Self Guided Historic Walking Tour |accessdate=May 23, 2019}}</ref> The ''St.'' was added to the name simply to make it sound more pleasing and the pluralization was in honour of the combined efforts of Jacob C. Snider (1791\u20131865) and his son, Jacob C. Snider, Jr. (1822\u20131857), founders of the village.<ref>[http://www.exploringontario.com/huron_perth_waterloo_wellington_region/st_jacobs_ontario.html Exploring Ontario: St. Jacobs]</ref> The first post office in St. Jacobs opened in 1852, called St. Jacobs and the village was incorporated in that year. By 1855, the population was 400.<ref name=\"StJacobs\"/>\n\nIn 1864, the vast majority of the Township was rural, with some small settlements. The only incorporated villages were St. Jacub's, Conestogo, Winterbourne and Elmira.<ref>{{cite book | title = County of Waterloo Gazetteer and General Business Directory, For 1864 | publisher = Mitchell & Co. | year = 1864 | url = http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/obj/001075/f2/e010780571_p2.pdf | pages = 61}}</ref> [[Mennonites]] formed a significant proportion of the population in the 1850s. Most were the so-called [[Pennsylvania Dutch]], not referring to the Netherlands but a misnomer for Deitsch or Deutsch (German). They became known as [[Old Order Mennonite]] due to their very conservative, traditional lifestyle. (Other Mennonites in the area now have a less conservative lifestyle.) <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.kanada-ontario.de/en/st_jacobs/ |title=St. Jacobs & the Waterloo Region, Ontario, Canada Welcome you|website=Canada Vacation Planner |accessdate=May 23, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |author=John Connon |url=https://books.google.com/?id=jWpRIAuScXMC&pg=PA12&dq=History+St.+Jacobs+Ontario#v=onepage&q=History%20St.%20Jacobs%20Ontario&f=false |title=The Early History of Elora, Ontario and Vicinity |accessdate=May 23, 2019|isbn = 9780889200128|year = 1975}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://gameo.org/index.php?title=West_Woolwich_Mennonite_Meetinghouse_(Elmira,_Ontario,_Canada) |title=West Woolwich Mennonite Meetinghouse (Elmira, Ontario, Canada) |website=Global Anabaptist Mennonite Encyclopedia Online (GAMEO) |accessdate=May 23, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gameo.org/index.php?title=Elmira_Mennonite_Meetinghouse_(Elmira,_Ontario,_Canada) |title=Elmira Mennonite Meetinghouse (Elmira, Ontario, Canada)|website=Global Anabaptist Mennonite Encyclopedia Online (GAMEO) |accessdate=May 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Church Elmira.jpg|thumb|right|St. James Lutheran Church, Elmira]]\nIn the early 1900s, Woolwich Township exhibited a strong German culture and those of German origin made up a third of the population in 1911. Because of increased immigration direct from Germany, Lutherans were the primary religious group by that time; there were nearly three times as many Lutherans as Mennonites.<ref>\n{{cite web |url=http://waterlooregionww1.uwaterloo.ca/category/pre-1914/ |title=Waterloo Region Pre-1914 |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=2015 |website=Waterloo Region WWI |publisher=University of Waterloo |access-date=20 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nA rail line did not reach St. Jacobs or Elmira until 1891.<ref name=\"StJacobs\"/> The Grand Trunk and the Canadian Pacific railways provided useful transportation and as a result, furniture manufacturing and other industries began to open in Elmira.\n\nDuring the 1960s, due to the poor disposal practices of chemical manufacturers, contamination seeped down to the aquifer in and around Elmira. This contamination forced local water wells to close in 1990. Water is now delivered via a pipeline from Waterloo and other near local areas.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.oag-bvg.gc.ca/internet/English/pet_128_e_28855.html |title=Clean-up of chemical contamination in Elmira, Ontario |publisher=Office of the Auditor General of Canada |archivedate=March 26, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110326153824/http://www.oag-bvg.gc.ca/internet/English/pet_128_e_28855.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.therecord.com/opinion-story/4959610-lessons-of-elmira-s-water-crisis-painful-costly/ |title=Lessons of Elmira's water crisis painful, costly |date=November 5, 2014 |first=Bob|last=Burtt |publisher=Waterloo Region Record |accessdate=May 23, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/kitchener-waterloo/ddt-levels-in-elmira-s-canagagigue-creek-much-higher-than-previously-thought-1.3187301 |title=DDT levels in Elmira's Canagagigue Creek much higher than previously thought |date=August 11, 2015|publisher=[[CBC News]] |accessdate=May 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Local Government==\nThe township is governed by an elected Mayor and five elected Councillors; two Councillors representing Wards 1 and 3, and one for Ward 2.<ref name=2018elec /> Council meetings are held in the Council Chambers at 24 Church Street West, Elmira.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.woolwich.ca/en/township-services/Council-Meetings.aspx |title=Council Meetings |publisher=Woolwich Township |accessdate=May 23, 2019}}</ref> The Mayor serves also as the Regional Councillor and sits on the various boards, including Waterloo North Hydro, Grand River Conservation Authority, Regional Library Board, Kiwanis Transit Board, Waterloo Region Community Housing Committee, Kissing Bridge Trailway Advisory Committee and Airport Master Plan Committee.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.woolwich.ca/en/township-services/Mayor-and-Council.aspx |title=Mayor and Council |publisher=Woolwich Township |accessdate=May 23, 2019}}</ref> After the election in 2018 the elected council members are:<ref name=2018elec />\n\n'''Mayor''': Sandy Shantz\n\n'''Councillors''':\n\n* Ward 1: Scott McMillan\n* Ward 1: Patrick Merlihan\n* Ward 2: Fred Redekop\n* Ward 3: Murray Martin\n* Ward 3: Larry Shantz\n\nWoolwich is one of seven municipalities that make up the Waterloo Regional Council. Members of the Regional Council serve a four-year term and Woolwich's representative is the Mayor alone<ref name=\":1\" />. The Waterloo Regional Council is made up of the Chair and eight Councillors, as well as the mayors of the seven municipalities: Cambridge, Kitchener, Waterloo, and the Townships of North Dumfries, Wellesley, Wilmot and Woolwich.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web |url=https://www.regionofwaterloo.ca/en/regional-government/council.aspx |title=Council |publisher=Region of Waterloo|accessdate=May 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Economy==\n[[File:St Jacobs Market.jpg|thumb|right|The St. Jacobs Market is a major tourist attraction]]\n\nElmira is the primary industrial centre of Woolwhich Township. Major employers include Trylon TSF,<ref>{{cite web |title=Contact |url=http://www.trylon.com/contact/ |publisher=Trylon TSF Inc. |accessdate=May 23, 2019}}</ref> Sanyo Machine Works, [[Elmira Pet Products]], Lanxess (formerly Chemtura and Uniroyal), Toyota Boshoku (formerly Trim Masters), [[Engineered Lifting Systems & Equipment Inc|Engineered Lifting Systems]], and Southfield Windows & Doors. Since the 1970s, [[tourism]] has become an increasingly important industry in Elmira and especially in [[St. Jacobs, Ontario|St. Jacobs]] which has a very popular [[St. Jacobs Farmers' Market|Farmers' Market]] and many quaint stores in its downtown area.<ref>{{cite web|last=Hohol |first=Frances (M.A. thesis) |date=1984 |url=http://scholars.wlu.ca/etd/296/ |publisher=Wilfrid Laurier University |title=Communities in transition: Elmira and St. Jacobs, Ontario: A study of resident and retailer attitudes toward tourism}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ontariotravel.net/en/explore/huron-perth-waterloo-and-wellington/st-jacobs-country |title=St. Jacobs|website=Ontariotravel.net|accessdate=May 23, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=St. Jacobs, Ontario, Canada|url=http://www.exchangemagazine.com/visitor/stjacobs/|publisher=Exchange Business Communications Inc.}}</ref>\n\nSt. Jacobs features dozens of artisans in historic buildings, such as the Country Mill, Village Silos, Mill Shed, and the Old Factory. Visitors may watch artisans make pottery, quilts, designer clothes, jewellery, glass vases, woven wall hangings tiffany lamps, stained glass doors, miniature doll houses and more. There are also two blacksmith shops. The two-kilometre millrace is a pleasant, treed hiking path along the Conestogo River. The Visitor Centre in downtown St. Jacobs is a Mennonite interpretation centre, providing information and education about the Mennonite people in the township.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.explorewaterlooregion.com/region-of-waterloo/township-of-woolwich/ |title=Township of Woolwich |website=ExploreWaterlooRegion.com |accessdate=May 23, 2019}}</ref>\n[[File:Home Hardware building St Jacobs Ontario.jpg|thumb|right|The original Home Hardware building]]\n\nSt. Jacobs is also the headquarters of [[Home Hardware]], a national chain of over 1000 independent hardware retail stores located across Canada that was founded in the village in 1963. The first store opened in St. Jacobs in 1964. It remains in use by the chain as the furniture outlet but a new store was built across the street, opening in November 2014.<ref>{{cite news |last=Walker |first=Philip |date=November 9, 2013 |title=Original Home Hardware store moves across the street |url=http://www.therecord.com/news-story/4201885-original-home-hardware-store-moves-across-the-street/ | work=Waterloo Region Record |location=Kitchener |access-date=March 22, 2017}}</ref>\n\nEconomic development for the township is handled by the Region of Waterloo. Elmira and St. Jacobs have their own Business Improvement Area committees.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.woolwich.ca/en/doing-business/Economic-Development-in-Waterloo-Region.aspx |title=Economic Development in Waterloo Region |publisher=Woolwich Township |accessdate=May 23, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.woolwich.ca/en/doing-business/Business-Improvement-Areas-BIAs.aspx |title=Business Improvement Areas (BIAs)|publisher=Woolwich Township |accessdate=May 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Education ==\nSchools in Woolwich are operated by the [[Waterloo Region District School Board]] and [[Waterloo Catholic District School Board]].<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.woolwich.ca/en/living-here/Schools-and-Education.aspx|title=Schools and Education|date=2016|website=woolwich.ca|access-date=December 14, 2018}}</ref> Woolwich has eight elementary schools, seven of which are public and one is Catholic.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.homenova.com/ca/on/woolwich|title=Community Profile for Woolwich, Ontario |date=2018|website=homenova.com|access-date=December 14, 2018}}</ref> [[Elmira District Secondary School]] is Woolwich's only secondary (high) school, but is ranked by [[Fraser Institute]] as a top Ontario high school.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ontario.compareschoolrankings.org/secondary/SchoolsByRankLocationName.aspx|title=Fraser Institute Ontario School Ranking|date=2016\u20132017|website=ontario.compareschoolrankings.org|access-date=December 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Communities==\n[[File:Elmira Street.jpg|thumb|right|Street scene in Elmira]]\n\nWoolwich consists of an extensive rural area along with residential communities and industrial/commercial areas. The residential communities include: [[Elmira, Ontario|Elmira]], [[St. Jacobs, Ontario|St. Jacobs]], [[Breslau, Ontario|Breslau]], [[Conestogo, Ontario|Conestogo]], Heidelberg, [[Maryhill, Ontario|Maryhill]], [[North Woolwich, Ontario|North Woolwich]], Bloomingdale, [[Weissenburg, Ontario|Weissenburg]], [[West Montrose, Ontario|West Montrose]], [[Floradale, Ontario|Floradale]], [[Winterbourne, Ontario|Winterbourne]], Crowsfoot Corners, Mundil, Weber, Shantz Station, Martin Grove Village, Eldale, and [[Zuber Corners, Ontario|Zuber Corners]].\n\nThe three largest areas offering a range of residential, industrial, commercial and recreational uses are in Elmira, St. Jacobs and Breslau; the latter adjoins Kitchener and is the fastest growing community in the township.\n\nWoolwich Township spans approximately 326.15 km\u00b2.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n== Infrastructure ==\n\n=== Health and Medicine ===\nWoolwich does not have its own hospitals, but residents of Woolwich have access to three nearby hospitals: [[Grand River Hospital]], [[St. Mary's General Hospital]] and [[Guelph General Hospital]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.woolwich.ca/en/living-here/Emergency-Services.aspx|title=Emergency Services|date=2016|website=woolwich.ca|access-date=December 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Transportation===\n'''Airport'''\n* [[Region of Waterloo International Airport]] (YKF), Breslau\n'''Bus'''  \n*[[Grand River Transit]] Bus 21 services Elmira and St.Jacobs\n'''Rail Services''' \n* CN Railway, South Woolwich (Breslau Area) Passenger/Freight\n* Region of Waterloo   Waterloo to Elmira   Freight\n'''Highways'''\n* [[Ontario Highway 7|Highway 7]]: Southern Portion of Woolwich (Breslau Area)\n* [[Ontario Highway 86|Highway 86]]: Entering Woolwich from the City of Waterloo\n* [[Ontario Highway 8|Highway 8]]: Approximately 20&nbsp;km (12 miles) to Elmira and 12&nbsp;km (7.5 miles) to the Woolwich boundary\n* [[Ontario Highway 401|Highway 401]]: Approximately 28&nbsp;km (17 miles) to Elmira and 20&nbsp;km (12 miles) to the woolwich boundary\n\n===Trails===\n\nWoolwich Township has eleven trails; much of the 45 kilometre long Kissing Bridge Trailway runs through this area.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.kissingbridgetrailway.ca/ |title=Kissing Bridge Trailway |accessdate=May 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Woolwich Memorial Centre===\nThe [[Woolwich Memorial Centre]] (WMC) is the Township of Woolwich's newest state-of-the-art facility comprising two NHL-sized ice surfaces, two pools, a fitness centre and walking track. The facility also includes a community centre, seniors centre, youth centre, Concourse Cafe, two meeting rooms and offices for minor sport teams.<ref>{{cite web |title=Woolwich Memorial Centre |url=https://www.woolwich.ca/en/living-here/woolwich-memorial-centre.aspx |publisher=Woolwich Township |accessdate=May 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Demographics==\nIn 2016, the average age in Woolwich was 39, with 49% of the population male and 51% female.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?B1=All&Code1=3530035&Code2=35&Data=Count&Geo1=CSD&Geo2=PR&Lang=E&SearchPR=01&SearchText=Woolwich&SearchType=Begins&TABID=1|title=Census Profile, 2016 Census Woolwich, Township|date=2016|website=statcan.gc.ca|access-date=December 14, 2018}}</ref> There are 8,741 total private dwellings, in 2016, and 98.5% (8,611) are occupied by usual residents.<ref name=\":4\" /> In 2016, English was the predominant language spoken at 88% of households, followed by German 8%, and Dutch 0.58%, which make up the top three most spoken languages in Woolwich.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n{{Historical populations\n|title = \n|type = Canada\n|align = right\n|width =\n|state =\n|shading =\n|percentages =\n|footnote = \n|1991|17365\n|[[1996 Canadian Census|1996]]|17325\n|[[2001 Canadian Census|2001]]|18201\n|[[2006 Canadian Census|2006]]|19658\n|[[2011 Canadian Census|2011]]|23145 \n|[[2016 Canadian Census|2016]]|25006 \n}}\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:West Montrose Covered Bridge, West Montrose, ON.jpg|West Montrose Covered bridge; Grand River\nFile:Church woolwich.jpg|Woolwich Countryside\nFile:Maryhillaerial.jpg|Maryhill, Woolwich\nFile:Woolwich_Trail.jpg|Woolwich Trail\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of townships in Ontario]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Woolwich, Ontario}}\n* [http://www.woolwich.ca/ Township of Woolwich]\n\n{{Geographic location\n | Centre    = Woolwich\n | North     = [[Centre Wellington, Ontario|Centre Wellington]]\n | Northeast = [[Guelph/Eramosa]]\n | East      = [[Puslinch, Ontario|Puslinch]]\n | Southeast = [[Cambridge, Ontario|Cambridge]]\n | South     = [[Waterloo, Ontario|Waterloo]], [[Kitchener, Ontario|Kitchener]]\n | Southwest = [[Wilmot, Ontario|Wilmot]]\n | West      = [[Wellesley, Ontario|Wellesley]]\n | Northwest = [[Mapleton, Ontario|Mapleton]]\n}}\n{{WaterlooRegion}}\n\n[[Category:Lower-tier municipalities in Ontario]]\n[[Category:Woolwich, Ontario| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n| name                            = Woolwich\n| official_name                   = Township of WoolWittch\n| settlement_type                 = [[List of township municipalities in Ontario|Township]] ([[List of municipalities in Ontario#Lower-tier municipalities|lower-tier]])\n| other_name                      = \n| native_name                     = <!-- for cities whose native name is not in English -->\n| nickname                        = \n| motto                           = \n| image_skyline                   = Aerial_Woolwich.jpg\n| image_caption                   = \n| image_flag                      = \n| flag_size                       = \n| image_seal                      = \n| seal_size                       = \n| image_shield                    = \n| shield_size                     = \n| image_blank_emblem              = \n| blank_emblem_size               = \n| image_map                       = \n| mapsize                         = \n| map_caption                     = \n| pushpin_map                     = Canada Southern Ontario\n| pushpin_label_position          = \n| pushpin_mapsize                 = 200\n| coordinates                     = {{coord|43|34|N|80|29|W|region:CA-ON|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type                = [[Countries of the world|Country]]\n| subdivision_name                = {{CAN}}\n| subdivision_type1               = [[Provinces and territories of Canada|Province]]\n| subdivision_name1               = {{ON}}\n| subdivision_type2               = [[Census divisions of Ontario|Regional municipality]]\n| subdivision_name2               = [[Regional Municipality of Waterloo|Waterloo]]\n| subdivision_type3               = \n| subdivision_name3               = \n| subdivision_type4               = \n| subdivision_name4               = \n| government_type                 = Township\n| leader_title                    = Mayor\n| leader_name                     = Sandy Shantz <ref name=2018elec>{{cite web |url= https://www.woolwich.ca/en/elections/resources/Woolwich-Township-2018-Election---Official-Results.pdf |title= Woolwich Township Official Election Results |publisher= Woolwich Township |accessdate=2018-12-14}}</ref>\n| leader_title1                   = Councillors\n| leader_name1                    = {{Collapsible list\n|title = List\n|frame_style = border:none; padding: 0;\n|list_style = text-align:left;display:none;\n|1= Scott Hahn\n|2= Patrick Merlihan\n|3= Fred Redekop\n|4= Murray Martin\n|5= Lary Shantz\n}}\n| leader_title2                   = Governing Body\n| leader_name2                    = Woolwich Township Council\n| leader_title3                   = [[House of Commons of Canada|MP]]\n| leader_name3                    = [[Harold Albrecht]] ([[Conservative Party of Canada|CPC]])\n| leader_title4                   = [[Legislative Assembly of Ontario|MPP]]\n| leader_name4                    = [[Mike Harris Jr. (politician)|Mike Harris Jr.]] ([[Ontario Progressive Conservative Party|PC]])\n| established_title               = Settled\n| established_date                = 1798\n| established_title2              = Incorporated\n| established_date2               = \n| established_title3              = \n| established_date3               = \n| area_magnitude                  = \n| area_footnotes                  = <ref name=\"cp2011\">{{cite web |url=http://www12.statcan.ca/census-recensement/2011/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CSD&Code1=3530035&Geo2=CD&Code2=3530&Data=Count&SearchText=Woolwich&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&Custom=&TABID=1 |title=Woolwich, Ontario (Code 3530035) census profile |publisher=Statistics Canada |work=[[Canada 2011 Census|2011 Census of Population]] |accessdate=2012-08-17}}</ref>\n| area_total_km2                  = \n| area_land_km2                   = 326.15\n| area_water_km2                  = \n| area_water_percent              = \n| population_as_of                = 2016\n| population_footnotes            = <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/dp-pd/prof/details/Page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CSD&Code1=3530035&Geo2=PR&Code2=47&Data=Count&SearchText=Waterloo&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All |title=Census Profile, 2016 Census: Woolwich, Township|publisher=Statistics Canada|accessdate=May 22, 2019}}</ref>\n| population_note                 = \n| population_total                = 25,006\n| population_density_km2          = 76.7\n| timezone                        = [[North American Eastern Time Zone|EST]]\n| utc_offset                      = -5\n| timezone_DST                    = [[Eastern Daylight Time|EDT]]\n| utc_offset_DST                  = -4\n| elevation_footnotes             = <!--for references: use <ref> </ref> tags-->\n| elevation_m                     = \n| postal_code_type                = Postal code span\n| postal_code                     = \n| area_code                       = [[Area codes 519 and 226|519 and 226]]\n| website                         = [http://www.woolwich.ca/ www.woolwich.ca]\n| footnotes                       = \n}}\n\n[[File:Woolwich Township, Ontario.PNG|thumb|Woolwich within Waterloo Region]]\nThe '''Township of Woolwich''' is a [[rural]] [[township (Canada)|township]] in [[Southwestern Ontario]], Canada, considered as a municipality. The Township is located in the northeast part of Waterloo Region and is made up of 10 small communities, with [[Elmira, Ontario]] the largest and [[St. Jacobs, Ontario]] the second largest. The population at the time of the 2016 Census was 25,006, up slightly from the 2011 population of 23,145. Waterloo Region is still home to the largest population of Old Order Mennonites in Canada, particularly in the areas around St Jacobs and Elmira.<ref name=\"OOM\">{{cite web |url=https://canadaalive.wordpress.com/2014/03/31/old-order-mennonites/ |title=Old Order Mennonites |website=Canada Alive!|date=March 31, 2014 |accessdate=May 22, 2019}}</ref> They are often seen on the local roads using their traditional horse and buggy transportation; many also use horses to pull the implements in their farm fields.<ref name=\"OOM\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://gameo.org/index.php?title=Old_Order_Mennonites |title=Old Order Mennonites |website=Global Anabaptist Mennonite Encyclopedia Online (GAMEO)|accessdate=May 22, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.woolwich.ca/en/discover-us/Tours-and-Self-Guided-Tours.aspx |title=Tours and Self-Guided Tours |publisher=Woolwich Township |accessdate=May 22, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.canadianmennonite.org/stories/old-order-mennonite-groups-ontario-are-growing |title=Old Order Mennonite groups in Ontario are growing |publisher=Canadian Mennonite Magazine |date=December 1, 2015 |first=Barb |last=Draper |accessdate=May 22, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.woolwich.ca/en/living-here/About-Woolwich.aspx |title=About Woolwich |publisher=Woolwich Township |accessdate=May 22, 2019}}</ref>\n\nWoolwich is part of the [[Regional Municipality of Waterloo]] and is located directly to the north and east of the [[Waterloo, Ontario|City of Waterloo]]. It is bounded by the cities of [[Kitchener, Ontario|Kitchener]], [[Waterloo, Ontario|Waterloo]], and [[Cambridge, Ontario|Cambridge]]. The township is a municipality as established by the Regional Municipality of Waterloo Act 1972, which created a regional government structure and established limits of the local municipalities effective January 1, 1973.  Woolwich Township has its own municipal government consisting of five Councillors and a Mayor; the latter also serves on the Waterloo Region Council.<ref name=\"MayorCouncil\">{{cite web |title=Mayor and Council |url=https://www.woolwich.ca/en/township-services/Mayor-and-Council.aspx |publisher=Woolwich Township |accessdate=May 22, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe land which now makes up Woolwich Township, with the Grand River on the East, and the Conestogo River on the West, originally belonged to the Huron Nation followed by the Mohawk Nation. The first settlers arrived in the late 18th century. In 1798, William Wallace was one of the first settlers after he was deeded 86,078 acres (348 km2) of land on the Grand River for a cost of $16,364. Originally Block three of Indian Lands, this area now comprises a large part of Woolwich Township. The parcel of land called \"Woolwich\" was probably named (in 1816) after a town in Kent, England. The early settlers were primarily from England or Ireland until about 1830; they settled to the east of the Grand River. Afterwards, German Mennonite families from Pennsylvania and from Waterloo Township settled west of the river.<ref>{{cite web |title=Woolwich Township |url=https://www.waterlooregionmuseum.ca/en/collections-and-research/woolwich-township.aspx |publisher=Ken Seiling Waterloo Region Museum |accessdate=May 22, 2019}} (section \"History of Woolwich Township\")</ref>\n\nIn 1807, Wallace sold the major portion of his tract to Mennonites from Pennsylvania, trustees for the German Company, many of whom would settle this area.<ref>{{cite book | title = County of Waterloo Gazetteer and General Business Directory, For 1864 | publisher = Mitchell & Co. | year = 1864 | url = http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/obj/001075/f2/e010780571_p2.pdf | pages = 61}}</ref> Wallace sold {{convert|45185|acre|km2|0}} of land to the German Company at $1.00 an acre. Captain Smith, a loyalist from Vermont, settled at the confluence of the Grand and Conestogo Rivers in 1807. Their large log home served as an inn for travelers and he operated a stagecoach for carrying mail from 1835 to 1850. The first church in Woolwich, was built by the Mennonites from Pennsylvania in approximately 1823 at the Three Bridges, now part of Conestogo.<ref name=\"WHSp16\">{{cite book |url=http://www.whs.ca/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/1933_V21.pdf |title=Twenty-first and Twenty-second Annual Reports |publisher=Waterloo Historical Society|page=16|accessdate=May 22, 2019}}</ref>  Woolwich was incorporated as a Township in 1816, and was part of Halton County until 1842 when it became part of Wellington District. In 1852, it became part of the new [[Waterloo County]].<ref>{{cite book |url=http://www.whs.ca/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/1933_V21.pdf |title=Twenty-first and Twenty-second Annual Reports |publisher=Waterloo Historical Society|pages=12\u201315|accessdate=May 22, 2019}}</ref>\n\nStarting in 1821, a part of Woolwich, to the east of the Grand River (Block 3), owned by James Crooks, attracted  dozens of families from England and Scotland. Previously, this area had few settlers, the most notable a Mr. Cox; the creek which enters the Grand River at what is now Winterbourne was named after him. Immigrants from Scotland began settling the Cox Creek area in 1834, led by John Davidson. He opened the first post office in the township, naming it East Woolwich. Captain Henry Lanphier arrived in 1854 and soon built a sawmill and flour mill after damming Cox Creek. Residents agreed with him that the settlement should be renamed [[Winterbourne, Ontario]]. By 1837, the Scots established St. Andrew's Presbyterian in 1837. A Presbyterian church was not built until 1870, made of logs; it was replaced in 1870 by one built of brick, and is currently a private home near the Winterbourne Presbyterian Cemetery. By 1867, Winterbourne  had a population of 160, three churches, a school, a post office, a general store, two mills, two hotels, two blacksmiths, a tailor, shoemaker and a physician.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Mills |first1=Rych |title=Flash from the Past: A Scottish enclave in Woolwich Township |url=https://www.therecord.com/living-story/7607547-flash-from-the-past-a-scottish-enclave-in-woolwich-township/ |accessdate=May 22, 2019 |work=Waterloo Region Record |publisher=Metroland News |date=October 13, 2017}}</ref>\n \nSt. Jacobs, like nearby Conestogo (both in Woolwich), was primarily Germanic and was first settled in 1830.<ref name=\"StJacobs\">{{cite web |title=Woolwich Township |url=https://www.waterlooregionmuseum.ca/en/collections-and-research/woolwich-township.aspx |publisher=Ken Seiling Waterloo Region Museum |accessdate=May 22, 2019}} (section \"St. Jacobs\")</ref> In 1834, Edward Bristow from Sussex, England<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mcburney.ca/mcburney/3252.htm |title=Hannah Streater|publisher=Lloyd McBurney |accessdate=May 22, 2019}}</ref> became one of Elmira's first settlers when he purchased {{convert|53|acre|m2}} of land at this location for 50 cents per acre. He started the first store, tavern and potashery.<ref>{{cite web |title=Elmira Travel Guide |url=http://www.elmira-on.worldweb.com/ |website=Worldweb.com |accessdate=May 23, 2019}}</ref> A community by the name of Bristow's Corners was already in existence in 1839 when a post office was assigned there; it was renamed Elmira in 1853.\n\n[[File:Mennonite carriage (cropped).jpg|thumb|right|Old Order Mennonite buggy still common in Woolwich Township]]\n\nHistorical records suggest that David Musselman founded Conestoga after buying land in 1830. He built a sawmill in 1844 and after damming the Conestoga River, he added a flour mill and a second sawmill. The hamlet formed in this area, known as Musselman's Mills until 1852 when it became Conestoga because many of the settlers had come from the Conestoga River area of Pennsylvania.<ref name=\"WHSp16\"/> Records about the entire township from 1846 indicate that the area was thinly settled although the land was excellent and there were large tracts of hardwood. There were two grist and two saw mills and an Episcopal church. The population count in 1841 indicated 1009 people.<ref>{{cite book |last=Smith |first=Wm. H. |date=1846 |title=Smith's Canadian Gazetteer - Statistical and General Information Respecting all parts of The Upper Province, or Canada West|url=https://archive.org/details/smithscanadianga00smit |location=Toronto |publisher=H. & W. Rowsell |pages=[https://archive.org/details/smithscanadianga00smit/page/223 223]\u2013224}}</ref>\n\nWoolwich Township Council was organized in January 1850 with five councillors, of whom John N. Meyer was named as Reeve; James Dow was appointed as clerk and treasurer.<ref>{{cite book |url=http://www.whs.ca/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/1933_V21.pdf |title=Twenty-first and Twenty-second Annual Reports |publisher=Waterloo Historical Society|page=14|accessdate=May 22, 2019}}</ref> A significant influx to the St. Jacobs area started afterwards, primarily consisting of additional Mennonites from Pennsylvania. Farmer and pioneer industrialist Jacob C. Snider, of Swiss German descent, was the most important settler at the time and the community was named after him: Jakobstettel (Jacob's Village). He built a dam to power several mills and then built a sawmill, woolen mill and flour mill by 1852. This helped to attract others to the small community.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Village of St. Jacobs: A Glimpse into Ontario's Mennonite Heritage|url=http://magiccarpetjournals.com/St_Jacobs.htm|publisher=Magic Carpet Journal}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.stjacobs.com/userContent/documents/Our%20Stories/SELFGUIDEDHISTORICWALKINGTOURWeb_000.pdf |title=St. Jacobs Self Guided Historic Walking Tour |accessdate=May 23, 2019}}</ref> The ''St.'' was added to the name simply to make it sound more pleasing and the pluralization was in honour of the combined efforts of Jacob C. Snider (1791\u20131865) and his son, Jacob C. Snider, Jr. (1822\u20131857), founders of the village.<ref>[http://www.exploringontario.com/huron_perth_waterloo_wellington_region/st_jacobs_ontario.html Exploring Ontario: St. Jacobs]</ref> The first post office in St. Jacobs opened in 1852, called St. Jacobs and the village was incorporated in that year. By 1855, the population was 400.<ref name=\"StJacobs\"/>\n\nIn 1864, the vast majority of the Township was rural, with some small settlements. The only incorporated villages were St. Jacub's, Conestogo, Winterbourne and Elmira.<ref>{{cite book | title = County of Waterloo Gazetteer and General Business Directory, For 1864 | publisher = Mitchell & Co. | year = 1864 | url = http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/obj/001075/f2/e010780571_p2.pdf | pages = 61}}</ref> [[Mennonites]] formed a significant proportion of the population in the 1850s. Most were the so-called [[Pennsylvania Dutch]], not referring to the Netherlands but a misnomer for Deitsch or Deutsch (German). They became known as [[Old Order Mennonite]] due to their very conservative, traditional lifestyle. (Other Mennonites in the area now have a less conservative lifestyle.) <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.kanada-ontario.de/en/st_jacobs/ |title=St. Jacobs & the Waterloo Region, Ontario, Canada Welcome you|website=Canada Vacation Planner |accessdate=May 23, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |author=John Connon |url=https://books.google.com/?id=jWpRIAuScXMC&pg=PA12&dq=History+St.+Jacobs+Ontario#v=onepage&q=History%20St.%20Jacobs%20Ontario&f=false |title=The Early History of Elora, Ontario and Vicinity |accessdate=May 23, 2019|isbn = 9780889200128|year = 1975}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://gameo.org/index.php?title=West_Woolwich_Mennonite_Meetinghouse_(Elmira,_Ontario,_Canada) |title=West Woolwich Mennonite Meetinghouse (Elmira, Ontario, Canada) |website=Global Anabaptist Mennonite Encyclopedia Online (GAMEO) |accessdate=May 23, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gameo.org/index.php?title=Elmira_Mennonite_Meetinghouse_(Elmira,_Ontario,_Canada) |title=Elmira Mennonite Meetinghouse (Elmira, Ontario, Canada)|website=Global Anabaptist Mennonite Encyclopedia Online (GAMEO) |accessdate=May 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Church Elmira.jpg|thumb|right|St. James Lutheran Church, Elmira]]\nIn the early 1900s, Woolwich Township exhibited a strong German culture and those of German origin made up a third of the population in 1911. Because of increased immigration direct from Germany, Lutherans were the primary religious group by that time; there were nearly three times as many Lutherans as Mennonites.<ref>\n{{cite web |url=http://waterlooregionww1.uwaterloo.ca/category/pre-1914/ |title=Waterloo Region Pre-1914 |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=2015 |website=Waterloo Region WWI |publisher=University of Waterloo |access-date=20 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nA rail line did not reach St. Jacobs or Elmira until 1891.<ref name=\"StJacobs\"/> The Grand Trunk and the Canadian Pacific railways provided useful transportation and as a result, furniture manufacturing and other industries began to open in Elmira.\n\nDuring the 1960s, due to the poor disposal practices of chemical manufacturers, contamination seeped down to the aquifer in and around Elmira. This contamination forced local water wells to close in 1990. Water is now delivered via a pipeline from Waterloo and other near local areas.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.oag-bvg.gc.ca/internet/English/pet_128_e_28855.html |title=Clean-up of chemical contamination in Elmira, Ontario |publisher=Office of the Auditor General of Canada |archivedate=March 26, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110326153824/http://www.oag-bvg.gc.ca/internet/English/pet_128_e_28855.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.therecord.com/opinion-story/4959610-lessons-of-elmira-s-water-crisis-painful-costly/ |title=Lessons of Elmira's water crisis painful, costly |date=November 5, 2014 |first=Bob|last=Burtt |publisher=Waterloo Region Record |accessdate=May 23, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/kitchener-waterloo/ddt-levels-in-elmira-s-canagagigue-creek-much-higher-than-previously-thought-1.3187301 |title=DDT levels in Elmira's Canagagigue Creek much higher than previously thought |date=August 11, 2015|publisher=[[CBC News]] |accessdate=May 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Local Government==\nThe township is governed by an elected Mayor and five elected Councillors; two Councillors representing Wards 1 and 3, and one for Ward 2.<ref name=2018elec /> Council meetings are held in the Council Chambers at 24 Church Street West, Elmira.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.woolwich.ca/en/township-services/Council-Meetings.aspx |title=Council Meetings |publisher=Woolwich Township |accessdate=May 23, 2019}}</ref> The Mayor serves also as the Regional Councillor and sits on the various boards, including Waterloo North Hydro, Grand River Conservation Authority, Regional Library Board, Kiwanis Transit Board, Waterloo Region Community Housing Committee, Kissing Bridge Trailway Advisory Committee and Airport Master Plan Committee.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.woolwich.ca/en/township-services/Mayor-and-Council.aspx |title=Mayor and Council |publisher=Woolwich Township |accessdate=May 23, 2019}}</ref> After the election in 2018 the elected council members are:<ref name=2018elec />\n\n'''Mayor''': Sandy Shantz\n\n'''Councillors''':\n\n* Ward 1: Scott McMillan\n* Ward 1: Patrick Merlihan\n* Ward 2: Fred Redekop\n* Ward 3: Murray Martin\n* Ward 3: Larry Shantz\n\nWoolwich is one of seven municipalities that make up the Waterloo Regional Council. Members of the Regional Council serve a four-year term and Woolwich's representative is the Mayor alone<ref name=\":1\" />. The Waterloo Regional Council is made up of the Chair and eight Councillors, as well as the mayors of the seven municipalities: Cambridge, Kitchener, Waterloo, and the Townships of North Dumfries, Wellesley, Wilmot and Woolwich.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web |url=https://www.regionofwaterloo.ca/en/regional-government/council.aspx |title=Council |publisher=Region of Waterloo|accessdate=May 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Economy==\n[[File:St Jacobs Market.jpg|thumb|right|The St. Jacobs Market is a major tourist attraction]]\n\nElmira is the primary industrial centre of Woolwhich Township. Major employers include Trylon TSF,<ref>{{cite web |title=Contact |url=http://www.trylon.com/contact/ |publisher=Trylon TSF Inc. |accessdate=May 23, 2019}}</ref> Sanyo Machine Works, [[Elmira Pet Products]], Lanxess (formerly Chemtura and Uniroyal), Toyota Boshoku (formerly Trim Masters), [[Engineered Lifting Systems & Equipment Inc|Engineered Lifting Systems]], and Southfield Windows & Doors. Since the 1970s, [[tourism]] has become an increasingly important industry in Elmira and especially in [[St. Jacobs, Ontario|St. Jacobs]] which has a very popular [[St. Jacobs Farmers' Market|Farmers' Market]] and many quaint stores in its downtown area.<ref>{{cite web|last=Hohol |first=Frances (M.A. thesis) |date=1984 |url=http://scholars.wlu.ca/etd/296/ |publisher=Wilfrid Laurier University |title=Communities in transition: Elmira and St. Jacobs, Ontario: A study of resident and retailer attitudes toward tourism}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ontariotravel.net/en/explore/huron-perth-waterloo-and-wellington/st-jacobs-country |title=St. Jacobs|website=Ontariotravel.net|accessdate=May 23, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=St. Jacobs, Ontario, Canada|url=http://www.exchangemagazine.com/visitor/stjacobs/|publisher=Exchange Business Communications Inc.}}</ref>\n\nSt. Jacobs features dozens of artisans in historic buildings, such as the Country Mill, Village Silos, Mill Shed, and the Old Factory. Visitors may watch artisans make pottery, quilts, designer clothes, jewellery, glass vases, woven wall hangings tiffany lamps, stained glass doors, miniature doll houses and more. There are also two blacksmith shops. The two-kilometre millrace is a pleasant, treed hiking path along the Conestogo River. The Visitor Centre in downtown St. Jacobs is a Mennonite interpretation centre, providing information and education about the Mennonite people in the township.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.explorewaterlooregion.com/region-of-waterloo/township-of-woolwich/ |title=Township of Woolwich |website=ExploreWaterlooRegion.com |accessdate=May 23, 2019}}</ref>\n[[File:Home Hardware building St Jacobs Ontario.jpg|thumb|right|The original Home Hardware building]]\n\nSt. Jacobs is also the headquarters of [[Home Hardware]], a national chain of over 1000 independent hardware retail stores located across Canada that was founded in the village in 1963. The first store opened in St. Jacobs in 1964. It remains in use by the chain as the furniture outlet but a new store was built across the street, opening in November 2014.<ref>{{cite news |last=Walker |first=Philip |date=November 9, 2013 |title=Original Home Hardware store moves across the street |url=http://www.therecord.com/news-story/4201885-original-home-hardware-store-moves-across-the-street/ | work=Waterloo Region Record |location=Kitchener |access-date=March 22, 2017}}</ref>\n\nEconomic development for the township is handled by the Region of Waterloo. Elmira and St. Jacobs have their own Business Improvement Area committees.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.woolwich.ca/en/doing-business/Economic-Development-in-Waterloo-Region.aspx |title=Economic Development in Waterloo Region |publisher=Woolwich Township |accessdate=May 23, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.woolwich.ca/en/doing-business/Business-Improvement-Areas-BIAs.aspx |title=Business Improvement Areas (BIAs)|publisher=Woolwich Township |accessdate=May 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Education ==\nSchools in Woolwich are operated by the [[Waterloo Region District School Board]] and [[Waterloo Catholic District School Board]].<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.woolwich.ca/en/living-here/Schools-and-Education.aspx|title=Schools and Education|date=2016|website=woolwich.ca|access-date=December 14, 2018}}</ref> Woolwich has eight elementary schools, seven of which are public and one is Catholic.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.homenova.com/ca/on/woolwich|title=Community Profile for Woolwich, Ontario |date=2018|website=homenova.com|access-date=December 14, 2018}}</ref> [[Elmira District Secondary School]] is Woolwich's only secondary (high) school, but is ranked by [[Fraser Institute]] as a top Ontario high school.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ontario.compareschoolrankings.org/secondary/SchoolsByRankLocationName.aspx|title=Fraser Institute Ontario School Ranking|date=2016\u20132017|website=ontario.compareschoolrankings.org|access-date=December 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Communities==\n[[File:Elmira Street.jpg|thumb|right|Street scene in Elmira]]\n\nWoolwich consists of an extensive rural area along with residential communities and industrial/commercial areas. The residential communities include: [[Elmira, Ontario|Elmira]], [[St. Jacobs, Ontario|St. Jacobs]], [[Breslau, Ontario|Breslau]], [[Conestogo, Ontario|Conestogo]], Heidelberg, [[Maryhill, Ontario|Maryhill]], [[North Woolwich, Ontario|North Woolwich]], Bloomingdale, [[Weissenburg, Ontario|Weissenburg]], [[West Montrose, Ontario|West Montrose]], [[Floradale, Ontario|Floradale]], [[Winterbourne, Ontario|Winterbourne]], Crowsfoot Corners, Mundil, Weber, Shantz Station, Martin Grove Village, Eldale, and [[Zuber Corners, Ontario|Zuber Corners]].\n\nThe three largest areas offering a range of residential, industrial, commercial and recreational uses are in Elmira, St. Jacobs and Breslau; the latter adjoins Kitchener and is the fastest growing community in the township.\n\nWoolwich Township spans approximately 326.15 km\u00b2.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n== Infrastructure ==\n\n=== Health and Medicine ===\nWoolwich does not have its own hospitals, but residents of Woolwich have access to three nearby hospitals: [[Grand River Hospital]], [[St. Mary's General Hospital]] and [[Guelph General Hospital]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.woolwich.ca/en/living-here/Emergency-Services.aspx|title=Emergency Services|date=2016|website=woolwich.ca|access-date=December 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Transportation===\n'''Airport'''\n* [[Region of Waterloo International Airport]] (YKF), Breslau\n'''Bus'''  \n*[[Grand River Transit]] Bus 21 services Elmira and St.Jacobs\n'''Rail Services''' \n* CN Railway, South Woolwich (Breslau Area) Passenger/Freight\n* Region of Waterloo   Waterloo to Elmira   Freight\n'''Highways'''\n* [[Ontario Highway 7|Highway 7]]: Southern Portion of Woolwich (Breslau Area)\n* [[Ontario Highway 86|Highway 86]]: Entering Woolwich from the City of Waterloo\n* [[Ontario Highway 8|Highway 8]]: Approximately 20&nbsp;km (12 miles) to Elmira and 12&nbsp;km (7.5 miles) to the Woolwich boundary\n* [[Ontario Highway 401|Highway 401]]: Approximately 28&nbsp;km (17 miles) to Elmira and 20&nbsp;km (12 miles) to the woolwich boundary\n\n===Trails===\n\nWoolwich Township has eleven trails; much of the 45 kilometre long Kissing Bridge Trailway runs through this area.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.kissingbridgetrailway.ca/ |title=Kissing Bridge Trailway |accessdate=May 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Woolwich Memorial Centre===\nThe [[Woolwich Memorial Centre]] (WMC) is the Township of Woolwich's newest state-of-the-art facility comprising two NHL-sized ice surfaces, two pools, a fitness centre and walking track. The facility also includes a community centre, seniors centre, youth centre, Concourse Cafe, two meeting rooms and offices for minor sport teams.<ref>{{cite web |title=Woolwich Memorial Centre |url=https://www.woolwich.ca/en/living-here/woolwich-memorial-centre.aspx |publisher=Woolwich Township |accessdate=May 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Demographics==\nIn 2016, the average age in Woolwich was 39, with 49% of the population male and 51% female.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?B1=All&Code1=3530035&Code2=35&Data=Count&Geo1=CSD&Geo2=PR&Lang=E&SearchPR=01&SearchText=Woolwich&SearchType=Begins&TABID=1|title=Census Profile, 2016 Census Woolwich, Township|date=2016|website=statcan.gc.ca|access-date=December 14, 2018}}</ref> There are 8,741 total private dwellings, in 2016, and 98.5% (8,611) are occupied by usual residents.<ref name=\":4\" /> In 2016, English was the predominant language spoken at 88% of households, followed by German 8%, and Dutch 0.58%, which make up the top three most spoken languages in Woolwich.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n{{Historical populations\n|title = \n|type = Canada\n|align = right\n|width =\n|state =\n|shading =\n|percentages =\n|footnote = \n|1991|17365\n|[[1996 Canadian Census|1996]]|17325\n|[[2001 Canadian Census|2001]]|18201\n|[[2006 Canadian Census|2006]]|19658\n|[[2011 Canadian Census|2011]]|23145 \n|[[2016 Canadian Census|2016]]|25006 \n}}\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:West Montrose Covered Bridge, West Montrose, ON.jpg|West Montrose Covered bridge; Grand River\nFile:Church woolwich.jpg|Woolwich Countryside\nFile:Maryhillaerial.jpg|Maryhill, Woolwich\nFile:Woolwich_Trail.jpg|Woolwich Trail\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of townships in Ontario]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Woolwich, Ontario}}\n* [http://www.woolwich.ca/ Township of Woolwich]\n\n{{Geographic location\n | Centre    = Woolwich\n | North     = [[Centre Wellington, Ontario|Centre Wellington]]\n | Northeast = [[Guelph/Eramosa]]\n | East      = [[Puslinch, Ontario|Puslinch]]\n | Southeast = [[Cambridge, Ontario|Cambridge]]\n | South     = [[Waterloo, Ontario|Waterloo]], [[Kitchener, Ontario|Kitchener]]\n | Southwest = [[Wilmot, Ontario|Wilmot]]\n | West      = [[Wellesley, Ontario|Wellesley]]\n | Northwest = [[Mapleton, Ontario|Mapleton]]\n}}\n{{WaterlooRegion}}\n\n[[Category:Lower-tier municipalities in Ontario]]\n[[Category:Woolwich, Ontario| ]]\n", "name_user": "Tga.D", "label": "safe", "comment": "linkOld Order Mennonitesin intro", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Woolwich,_Ontario"}
{"title_page": "The Ruby (EP)", "text_new": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = The Ruby\n| type       = EP\n| artist     = [[April (band)|April]]\n| cover      = April \u2013 The Ruby.png\n| alt        =\n| released   = {{Start date|2018|10|16}}\n| recorded   = 2018\n| studio     =\n| genre      = {{hlist|[[retro]]|[[dance-pop]]|[[synth-pop]]}}\n| length     = {{duration|m=16|s=26}}\n| language   = Korean\n| label      = {{hlist|[[DSP Media]]|[[Kakao M]]}}\n| producer   = \n| prev_title = [[The Blue (April EP)|The Blue]]\n| prev_year  = 2018\n| next_title = Da Capo \n| next_year  = 2020\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = The Ruby\n | type        = EP\n | single1     = Oh! My Mistake\n | single1date = October 16, 2018\n}}\n}}\n'''''The Ruby''''' is the sixth EP by South Korean girl group [[April (girl group)|April]]. It was released on October 16, 2018, by [[DSP Media]]. The EP was supported by the \"retro\" lead single \"Oh! My Mistake\".<ref name=\"Billboard\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/k-town/8480364/k-pop-girl-group-april-oh-my-mistake-retro-video|title=K-pop Girl Group April Turn up the Retro In 'Oh! My Mistake' Music Video: Watch|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|last=Herman|first=Tamar|date=October 17, 2018|accessdate=November 15, 2018}}</ref> ''The Ruby'' debuted and peaked at number 10 on the [[Gaon Album Chart]].\n\n==Background and release==\n[[DSP Media]] announced the band's comeback for October 16, 2018 on October 4.<ref name=\"Osen\">{{cite web|url=http://www.osen.co.kr/article/G1111001683|title=\"\uccad\uc815\ub3cc\uc758 \ubcc0\uc2e0\"\u2026\uc5d0\uc774\ud504\ub9b4, 16\uc77c 'the Ruby'\ub85c \uac00\uc694\uacc4 \ucef4\ubc31 [\uacf5\uc2dd\uc785\uc7a5]|trans-title=\"Transformation of clean stone\" ... Apr. 16, 'The Ruby' comeback comeback [official position]|publisher=Osen|last=Jeong|first=Jeewon|date=October 4, 2018|accessdate=November 15, 2018}}</ref> Being in black and white, Osen noted that the promotional poster differed from April's previous imagery as it lacked any primary colors, and noted that the band had evolved and matured with each release, \"adding a variety of changes to every album\".<ref name=\"Osen\"/> Several other publications also noted the change in style.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.yonhapnews.co.kr/bulletin/2018/10/04/0200000000AKR20181004050400005.HTML?input=1195m|title=\uc5d0\uc774\ud504\ub9b4, \uc0c8 \uc568\ubc94 '\ub354 \ub8e8\ube44'\ub85c 16\uc77c \ucef4\ubc31|trans-title=Apr, 16th comeback with new album 'The Ruby'|publisher=[[Yonhap]]|date=October 4, 2018|accessdate=November 15, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.chosun.com/news/ntype.htm?id=201810040100030700002202&servicedate=20181004|title=[\uacf5\uc2dd] \"\ud655 \ub2ec\ub77c\uc84c\ub2e4\"\u2026\uc5d0\uc774\ud504\ub9b4, 10\uc6d4 16\uc77c 'the Ruby'\ub85c \ucef4\ubc31 \ud655\uc815|trans-title=[Official] \"Changed\" ... APRIL, Oct. 16 Confirmed as 'The Ruby'|work=[[The Chosun Ilbo|Chosun]]|date=October 4, 2018|accessdate=November 15, 2018}}</ref>\n\n\"Oh! My Mistake\" was released along with the EP on October 16, with ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' calling it a \"revitalizing dance track that adds a new side to April's artistry\", as well as \"unconventional\" and describing it as having a \"rollicking '80s-esque scattered beat and quirky, cloying lo-fi vocals over vibrant synths\".<ref name=\"Billboard\"/> The magazine also said the video \"takes the audience back to the yesteryears of VHS tapes, corded phones, and [[Motorola Razr|RAZRs]]\".<ref name=\"Billboard\"/>\n\n==Music==\nThe EP opens with \"Oh-e-Oh\", an upbeat tropical song, followed by the lead single \"Oh! My Mistake\", an \"unconventional\" retro dance track. \"Story\", the third song, was called a \"whimsical, retro synth-pop tune\", and the last original song on the album, \"Love Clock\", is a pop rock track about the passage of time.<ref name=\"Billboard\"/>\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n| title1 = Oh-e-Oh\n| length1 = 3:12\n| title2 = Oh! My Mistake\n| length2 = 3:25\n| title3 = Story\n| length3 = 3:06\n| title4 = Love Clock\n| length4 = 3:18\n| title5 = Oh! My Mistake\n| note5 = instrumental\n| length5 = 3:25\n| total_length = 16:26\n}}\n\n==Charts==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (2018)\n! scope=\"col\"| Peak<br />position\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| South Korean Albums ([[Gaon Album Chart|Gaon]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gaonchart.co.kr/main/section/chart/album.gaon?nationGbn=T&serviceGbn=&targetTime=42&hitYear=2018&termGbn=week|title=Gaon Album Chart \u2013 Week 42, 2018|website=[[Gaon Music Chart|Gaon Chart]]|language=ko|accessdate=November 15, 2018}}</ref>\n| 10\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{April (band)}}\n\n[[Category:2018 EPs]]\n[[Category:April (band) albums]]\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ruby}}\n{{ep-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = The Ruby\n| type       = EP\n| artist     = [[April (band)|April]]\n| cover      = April \u2013 The Ruby.png\n| alt        =\n| released   = {{Start date|2018|10|16}}\n| recorded   = 2018\n| studio     =\n| genre      = {{hlist|[[retro]]|[[dance-pop]]|[[synth-pop]]}}\n| length     = {{duration|m=16|s=26}}\n| language   = Korean\n| label      = {{hlist|[[DSP Media]]|[[Kakao M]]}}\n| producer   = \n| prev_title = [[The Blue (April EP)|The Blue]]\n| prev_year  = 2018\n| next_title = Da Capo \n| next_year  = 2020\n| misc       =\n}}\n'''''The Ruby''''' is the sixth EP by South Korean girl group [[April (girl group)|April]]. It was released on October 16, 2018, by [[DSP Media]]. The EP was supported by the \"retro\" lead single \"Oh! My Mistake\".<ref name=\"Billboard\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/k-town/8480364/k-pop-girl-group-april-oh-my-mistake-retro-video|title=K-pop Girl Group April Turn up the Retro In 'Oh! My Mistake' Music Video: Watch|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|last=Herman|first=Tamar|date=October 17, 2018|accessdate=November 15, 2018}}</ref> ''The Ruby'' debuted and peaked at number 10 on the [[Gaon Album Chart]].\n\n==Background and release==\n[[DSP Media]] announced the band's comeback for October 16, 2018 on October 4.<ref name=\"Osen\">{{cite web|url=http://www.osen.co.kr/article/G1111001683|title=\"\uccad\uc815\ub3cc\uc758 \ubcc0\uc2e0\"\u2026\uc5d0\uc774\ud504\ub9b4, 16\uc77c 'the Ruby'\ub85c \uac00\uc694\uacc4 \ucef4\ubc31 [\uacf5\uc2dd\uc785\uc7a5]|trans-title=\"Transformation of clean stone\" ... Apr. 16, 'The Ruby' comeback comeback [official position]|publisher=Osen|last=Jeong|first=Jeewon|date=October 4, 2018|accessdate=November 15, 2018}}</ref> Being in black and white, Osen noted that the promotional poster differed from April's previous imagery as it lacked any primary colors, and noted that the band had evolved and matured with each release, \"adding a variety of changes to every album\".<ref name=\"Osen\"/> Several other publications also noted the change in style.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.yonhapnews.co.kr/bulletin/2018/10/04/0200000000AKR20181004050400005.HTML?input=1195m|title=\uc5d0\uc774\ud504\ub9b4, \uc0c8 \uc568\ubc94 '\ub354 \ub8e8\ube44'\ub85c 16\uc77c \ucef4\ubc31|trans-title=Apr, 16th comeback with new album 'The Ruby'|publisher=[[Yonhap]]|date=October 4, 2018|accessdate=November 15, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.chosun.com/news/ntype.htm?id=201810040100030700002202&servicedate=20181004|title=[\uacf5\uc2dd] \"\ud655 \ub2ec\ub77c\uc84c\ub2e4\"\u2026\uc5d0\uc774\ud504\ub9b4, 10\uc6d4 16\uc77c 'the Ruby'\ub85c \ucef4\ubc31 \ud655\uc815|trans-title=[Official] \"Changed\" ... APRIL, Oct. 16 Confirmed as 'The Ruby'|work=[[The Chosun Ilbo|Chosun]]|date=October 4, 2018|accessdate=November 15, 2018}}</ref>\n\n\"Oh! My Mistake\" was released along with the EP on October 16, with ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' calling it a \"revitalizing dance track that adds a new side to April's artistry\", as well as \"unconventional\" and describing it as having a \"rollicking '80s-esque scattered beat and quirky, cloying lo-fi vocals over vibrant synths\".<ref name=\"Billboard\"/> The magazine also said the video \"takes the audience back to the yesteryears of VHS tapes, corded phones, and [[Motorola Razr|RAZRs]]\".<ref name=\"Billboard\"/>\n\n==Music==\nThe EP opens with \"Oh-e-Oh\", an upbeat tropical song, followed by the lead single \"Oh! My Mistake\", an \"unconventional\" retro dance track. \"Story\", the third song, was called a \"whimsical, retro synth-pop tune\", and the last original song on the album, \"Love Clock\", is a pop rock track about the passage of time.<ref name=\"Billboard\"/>\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n| title1 = Oh-e-Oh\n| length1 = 3:12\n| title2 = Oh! My Mistake\n| length2 = 3:25\n| title3 = Story\n| length3 = 3:06\n| title4 = Love Clock\n| length4 = 3:18\n| title5 = Oh! My Mistake\n| note5 = instrumental\n| length5 = 3:25\n| total_length = 16:26\n}}\n\n==Charts==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (2018)\n! scope=\"col\"| Peak<br />position\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| South Korean Albums ([[Gaon Album Chart|Gaon]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gaonchart.co.kr/main/section/chart/album.gaon?nationGbn=T&serviceGbn=&targetTime=42&hitYear=2018&termGbn=week|title=Gaon Album Chart \u2013 Week 42, 2018|website=[[Gaon Music Chart|Gaon Chart]]|language=ko|accessdate=November 15, 2018}}</ref>\n| 10\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{April (band)}}\n\n[[Category:2018 EPs]]\n[[Category:April (band) albums]]\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ruby}}\n{{ep-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Porcelynne", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Ruby_(EP)"}
{"title_page": "Chris Kenner", "text_new": "{{for|the American close-up magician|Chris Kenner (magician)}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2014}}\n{{Infobox musical artist  <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name                = Chris Kenner\n| image               = Image:Chris kenner.jpg\n| caption             = \n| image_size          = \n| background          = solo_singer\n| birth_name          = Christophe Kenner\n| alias               = \n| birth_date          = {{birth date|1929|12|25|mf=y}}\n| birth_place         = [[Kenner, Louisiana|Kenner]], Louisiana, United States\n| death_date          = {{death date and age|1976|1|25|1929|12|25|mf=y}}\n| death_place         = [[New Orleans]], Louisiana, U.S.\n| origin              =\n| instrument          = Vocals\n| genre               = [[Rhythm and blues|R&B]]\n| occupation          = Singer, songwriter\n| years_active        = \n| label               = \n| associated_acts     = \n| website             =\n}}\n\n'''Christophe Kenner''' (December 25, 1929 \u2013 January 25, 1976) was an American, [[New Orleans]]-based [[Rhythm and blues|R&B]] singer and songwriter,<ref name=\"AMG\">{{cite web|author=Bill Dahl |url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/chris-kenner-mn0000774956/biography |title=Chris Kenner &#124; Biography & History |website=[[AllMusic]] |date= |accessdate=2020-04-10}}</ref> best known for two hit singles in the early 1960s, \"[[I Like It Like That (Chris Kenner song)|I Like It Like That]]\" and \"[[Land of a Thousand Dances|Land of 1000 Dances]]\", which became staples in the repertoires of many other musicians.\n\n==Biography==\nBorn in the farming community of [[Kenner, Louisiana]], upriver from New Orleans,<ref name=\"Way\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.waybackattack.com/kennerchris.html|title=Chris Kenner &#124; Way Back Attack|website=Waybackattack.com|accessdate=2020-04-10}}</ref> Kenner sang [[gospel music]] with his church choir. He moved to New Orleans when he was in his teens, to work as a [[longshoreman]].<ref name=\"black cat\"/> \n\nIn 1955 he made his first recordings, for a small label, [[Baton Records]], without success. In 1957, he recorded his \"[[Sick and Tired (Chris Kenner song)|Sick and Tired]]\" for [[Imperial Records]].<ref name=\"Way\"/> Kenner's recording reached number 13 on the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[R&B chart]].<ref name=\"whitburnr&b\">{{cite book |title=Top R&B/Hip-Hop Singles: 1942-1995 |last=Whitburn |first=Joel |authorlink=Joel Whitburn |year=1996 |publisher=Record Research |isbn=0-89820-115-2 |page=242}}</ref> [[Fats Domino]] covered it the next year, and his version became a hit on the pop chart.<ref name=\"AMG\"/> \"Rocket to the Moon\" and \"Life Is Just a Struggle\", both cut for Ron Records, were other notable songs Kenner recorded in this period.<ref name=\"Way\"/>\n\nMoving to another New Orleans label, [[Instant Records|Instant]] (which was initially called 'Valiant' before they discovered the name was already in use),<ref name=\"Way\"/> he began to work with the pianist and arranger [[Allen Toussaint]].<ref name=\"AMG\"/> In 1961, this collaboration produced \"[[I Like It Like That (Chris Kenner song)|I Like It Like That]]\", his biggest and first pop hit,<ref name=\"AMG\"/> peaking at number 2 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] chart (covered in 1965 by the [[The Dave Clark Five|Dave Clark Five]]), and \"Something You Got\" (covered by [[Wilson Pickett]], [[Alvin Robinson (musician)|Alvin Robinson]], the [[Ramsey Lewis]] Trio, [[Johnny Rivers]], [[Chuck Jackson]], [[Earl Grant]], [[Maxine Brown (soul singer)|Maxine Brown]], [[Fats Domino]], [[Bobby Womack]], [[The Moody Blues]], the [[The American Breed|American Breed]], [[Fairport Convention]], [[Bruce Springsteen]] and [[Jimi Hendrix]] (1966)). \"I Like It Like That\" sold over one million copies, was nominated for a [[Grammy Award|Grammy]],<ref name=\"black cat\"/> and was awarded a [[music recording sales certification|gold disc]] by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]].<ref name=\"The Book of Golden Discs\">{{cite book\n| first= Joseph\n| last= Murrells\n| year= 1978\n| title= The Book of Golden Discs\n| edition= 2nd\n| publisher= Barrie and Jenkins\n| location= London\n| page= [https://archive.org/details/bookofgoldendisc00murr/page/136 136]\n| isbn= 0-214-20512-6\n| url= https://archive.org/details/bookofgoldendisc00murr/page/136\n}}</ref>   \n\nKenner's song \u201cSomething You Got\u201d later became a hit for [[Alvin Robinson]], the [[Ramsey Lewis Trio]] and the duo of [[Chuck Jackson]] and [[Maxine Brown (soul singer)|Maxine Brown]].<ref name=\"black cat\"/>  In 1963 he released his most enduring song, \"[[Land of a Thousand Dances|Land of 1000 Dances]]\",<ref name=\"AMG\"/> based on an old [[Spiritual (music)|spiritual]].  Kenner's version reached number 77 on the pop chart in 1963.  It was later covered by various artists, including [[Cannibal & the Headhunters]], [[Fats Domino]], [[Thee Midniters]], [[Wilson Pickett]], the [[The Action|Action]], and [[Patti Smith]].   Kenner continued to record for Instant and for other small local labels, including many of his lesser-known songs from the 1960s, such as \"My Wife\", \"Packing Up\" and \"They Took My Money\". He released an album, ''Land of 1000 Dances'', on [[Atlantic Records]] in 1966;<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.toppermost.co.uk/chris-kenner/|title=Chris Kenner|website=Toppermost.co.uk|date=March 27, 2017|accessdate=2020-04-10}}</ref> it was reissued on CD by Collectors' Choice in 2007.\n\nKenner's career was affected by his unpredictable behavior &ndash; he drank and spent heavily, and would sometimes miss shows or forget the words to his songs.<ref name=\"black cat\"/>   He continued to record until 1968, with diminishing success.  In 1968, Kenner was convicted of [[statutory rape]] of a minor and spent three years in Louisiana's [[Louisiana State Penitentiary|Angola]] prison.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Lichtenstein|first1=Grace|last2=Dankner|first2=Laura|title=Musical Gumbo: The Music of New Orleans|url=https://archive.org/details/musicalgumbomusi00lich|url-access=registration|year=1993|publisher=W.W. Norton|isbn=978-0-393-03468-4|page=[https://archive.org/details/musicalgumbomusi00lich/page/117 117]}}</ref>\n\nKenner died from a heart attack in 1976, at the age of 46, triggered by alcoholism.<ref name=\"black cat\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rockabilly.nl/references/messages/chris_kenner.htm|title=CHRIS KENNER|website=Rockabilly.nl|accessdate=October 24, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Chart singles==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Year\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Single\n! colspan=\"2\"| Chart Positions\n|- style=\"font-size:smaller;\"\n! width=\"40\"| [[Billboard Hot 100|US Pop]]<ref>{{cite book|first=Joel|last=Whitburn|year=2003|title=Top Pop Singles 1955-2002|edition=1st|publisher=Record Research Inc.|location=Menomonee Falls, Wisconsin|isbn=0-89820-155-1|page=379}}</ref>\n! width=\"40\"| [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs|US<br>R&B]]<ref name=\"whitburnr&b\"/>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\"| 1957\n| align=\"left\"| \"[[Sick and Tired (Chris Kenner song)|Sick and Tired]]\"\n| -\n| 13\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\"| 1961\n| align=\"left\"| \"[[I Like It Like That (Chris Kenner song)|I Like It Like That]]\"\n| 2\n| 2\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\"| 1963\n| align=\"left\"| \"[[Land of a Thousand Dances|Land of 1000 Dances]]\"\n| 77\n| -\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.tsimon.com/land.htm ''Land of 1000 Dances'']\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kenner, Chris}}\n[[Category:1929 births]]\n[[Category:1976 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Kenner, Louisiana]]\n[[Category:African-American singers]]\n[[Category:American rhythm and blues singers]]\n[[Category:Rhythm and blues musicians from New Orleans]]\n[[Category:Songwriters from Louisiana]]\n[[Category:Singers from Louisiana]]\n[[Category:Atlantic Records artists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American singers]]\n[[Category:People convicted of statutory rape offenses]]\n[[Category:Alcohol-related deaths in Louisiana]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the American close-up magician|Chris Kenner (magician)}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2014}}\n{{Infobox musical artist  <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name                = Chris Kenner\n| image               = Image:Chris kenner.jpg\n| caption             = \n| image_size          = \n| background          = solo_singer\n| birth_name          = Christophe Kenner\n| alias               = \n| birth_date          = {{birth date|1929|12|25|mf=y}}\n| birth_place         = [[Kenner, Louisiana|Kenner]], Louisiana, United States\n| death_date          = {{death date and age|1976|1|25|1929|12|25|mf=y}}\n| death_place         = [[New Orleans]], Louisiana, U.S.\n| origin              =\n| instrument          = Vocals\n| genre               = [[Rhythm and blues|R&B]]\n| occupation          = Singer, songwriter\n| years_active        = \n| label               = \n| associated_acts     = \n| website             =\n}}\n\n'''Christophe Kenner''' (December 25, 1929 \u2013 January 25, 1976) was an American, [[New Orleans]]-based [[Rhythm and blues|R&B]] singer and songwriter,<ref name=\"AMG\">{{cite web|author=Bill Dahl |url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/chris-kenner-mn0000774956/biography |title=Chris Kenner &#124; Biography & History |website=[[AllMusic]] |date= |accessdate=2020-04-10}}</ref> best known for two hit singles in the early 1960s, \"[[I Like It Like That (Chris Kenner song)|I Like It Like That]]\" and \"[[Land of a Thousand Dances|Land of 1000 Dances]]\", which became staples in the repertoires of many other musicians.\n\n==Biography==\nBorn in the farming community of [[Kenner, Louisiana]], upriver from New Orleans,<ref name=\"Way\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.waybackattack.com/kennerchris.html|title=Chris Kenner &#124; Way Back Attack|website=Waybackattack.com|accessdate=2020-04-10}}</ref> Kenner sang [[gospel music]] with his church choir. He moved to New Orleans when he was in his teens, to work as a [[longshoreman]].<ref name=\"black cat\"/> \n\nIn 1955 he made his first recordings, for a small label, [[Baton Records]], without success. In 1957, he recorded his \"[[Sick and Tired (Chris Kenner song)|Sick and Tired]]\" for [[Imperial Records]].<ref name=\"Way\"/> Kenner's recording reached number 13 on the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[R&B chart]].<ref name=\"whitburnr&b\">{{cite book |title=Top R&B/Hip-Hop Singles: 1942-1995 |last=Whitburn |first=Joel |authorlink=Joel Whitburn |year=1996 |publisher=Record Research |isbn=0-89820-115-2 |page=242}}</ref> [[Fats Domino]] covered it the next year, and his version became a hit on the pop chart.<ref name=\"AMG\"/> \"Rocket to the Moon\" and \"Life Is Just a Struggle\", both cut for Ron Records, were other notable songs Kenner recorded in this period.<ref name=\"Way\"/>\n\nMoving to another New Orleans label, [[Instant Records|Instant]] (which was initially called 'Valiant' before they discovered the name was already in use),<ref name=\"Way\"/> he began to work with the pianist and arranger [[Allen Toussaint]].<ref name=\"AMG\"/> In 1961, this collaboration produced \"[[I Like It Like That (Chris Kenner song)|I Like It Like That]]\", his biggest and first pop hit,<ref name=\"AMG\"/> peaking at number 2 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] chart (covered in 1965 by the [[The Dave Clark Five|Dave Clark Five]]), and \"Something You Got\" (covered by [[Wilson Pickett]], [[Alvin Robinson (musician)|Alvin Robinson]], the [[Ramsey Lewis]] Trio, [[Johnny Rivers]], [[Chuck Jackson]], [[Earl Grant]], [[Maxine Brown (soul singer)|Maxine Brown]], [[Fats Domino]], [[Bobby Womack]], [[The Moody Blues]], the [[The American Breed|American Breed]], [[Fairport Convention]], [[Bruce Springsteen]] and [[Jimi Hendrix]] (1966)). \"I Like It Like That\" sold over one million copies, was nominated for a [[Grammy Award|Grammy]],<ref name=\"black cat\"/> and was awarded a [[music recording sales certification|gold disc]] by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]].<ref name=\"The Book of Golden Discs\">{{cite book\n| first= Joseph\n| last= Murrells\n| year= 1978\n| title= The Book of Golden Discs\n| edition= 2nd\n| publisher= Barrie and Jenkins\n| location= London\n| page= [https://archive.org/details/bookofgoldendisc00murr/page/136 136]\n| isbn= 0-214-20512-6\n| url= https://archive.org/details/bookofgoldendisc00murr/page/136\n}}</ref>   \n\nKenner's song \u201cSomething You Got\u201d later became a hit for [[Alvin Robinson]], the [[Ramsey Lewis Trio]] and the duo of [[Chuck Jackson]] and [[Maxine Brown (soul singer)|Maxine Brown]].<ref name=\"black cat\"/>  In 1963 he released his most enduring song, \"[[Land of a Thousand Dances|Land of 1000 Dances]]\",<ref name=\"AMG\"/> based on an old [[Spiritual (music)|spiritual]].  Kenner's version reached number 77 on the pop chart in 1963.  It was later covered by various artists, including [[Cannibal & the Headhunters]], [[Fats Domino]], [[Thee Midniters]], [[Wilson Pickett]], the [[The Action|Action]], and [[Patti Smith]].   Kenner continued to record for Instant and for other small local labels, including many of his lesser-known songs from the 1960s, such as \"My Wife\", \"Packing Up\" and \"They Took My Money\". He released an album, ''Land of 1000 Dances'', on [[Atlantic Records]] in 1966;<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.toppermost.co.uk/chris-kenner/|title=Chris Kenner|website=Toppermost.co.uk|date=March 27, 2017|accessdate=2020-04-10}}</ref> it was reissued on CD by Collectors' Choice in 2007.\n\nKenner's career was affected by his unpredictable behavior &ndash; he drank and spent heavily, and would sometimes miss shows or forget the words to his songs.<ref name=\"black cat\"/>   He continued to record until 1968, with diminishing success.  In 1968, Kenner was convicted of statutory rape of a minor and spent three years in Louisiana's [[Louisiana State Penitentiary|Angola]] prison.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Lichtenstein|first1=Grace|last2=Dankner|first2=Laura|title=Musical Gumbo: The Music of New Orleans|url=https://archive.org/details/musicalgumbomusi00lich|url-access=registration|year=1993|publisher=W.W. Norton|isbn=978-0-393-03468-4|page=[https://archive.org/details/musicalgumbomusi00lich/page/117 117]}}</ref>\n\nKenner died from a heart attack in 1976, at the age of 46, triggered by alcoholism.<ref name=\"black cat\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rockabilly.nl/references/messages/chris_kenner.htm|title=CHRIS KENNER|website=Rockabilly.nl|accessdate=October 24, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Chart singles==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Year\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Single\n! colspan=\"2\"| Chart Positions\n|- style=\"font-size:smaller;\"\n! width=\"40\"| [[Billboard Hot 100|US Pop]]<ref>{{cite book|first=Joel|last=Whitburn|year=2003|title=Top Pop Singles 1955-2002|edition=1st|publisher=Record Research Inc.|location=Menomonee Falls, Wisconsin|isbn=0-89820-155-1|page=379}}</ref>\n! width=\"40\"| [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs|US<br>R&B]]<ref name=\"whitburnr&b\"/>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\"| 1957\n| align=\"left\"| \"[[Sick and Tired (Chris Kenner song)|Sick and Tired]]\"\n| -\n| 13\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\"| 1961\n| align=\"left\"| \"[[I Like It Like That (Chris Kenner song)|I Like It Like That]]\"\n| 2\n| 2\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\"| 1963\n| align=\"left\"| \"[[Land of a Thousand Dances|Land of 1000 Dances]]\"\n| 77\n| -\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.tsimon.com/land.htm ''Land of 1000 Dances'']\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kenner, Chris}}\n[[Category:1929 births]]\n[[Category:1976 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Kenner, Louisiana]]\n[[Category:African-American singers]]\n[[Category:American rhythm and blues singers]]\n[[Category:Rhythm and blues musicians from New Orleans]]\n[[Category:Songwriters from Louisiana]]\n[[Category:Singers from Louisiana]]\n[[Category:Atlantic Records artists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American singers]]\n[[Category:People convicted of statutory rape offenses]]\n[[Category:Alcohol-related deaths in Louisiana]]\n", "name_user": "Ghmyrtle", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBiography", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chris_Kenner"}
{"title_page": "Ron Tugnutt", "text_new": "{{Infobox ice hockey player\n| position = [[Goaltender]]\n| catches = Left\n| height_ft = 5\n| height_in = 04\n| weight_lb = 165\n| played_for = '''[[American Hockey League|AHL]]'''<br>[[Fredericton Express]]<br>[[Halifax Citadels]]<br>[[Portland Pirates]]<br>'''[[National Hockey League|NHL]]'''<br>[[Quebec Nordiques]]<br />[[Edmonton Oilers]]<br />[[Mighty Ducks of Anaheim]]<br />[[Montreal Canadiens]]<br />[[Ottawa Senators]]<br />[[Pittsburgh Penguins]]<br />[[Columbus Blue Jackets]]<br />[[Dallas Stars]]\n| ntl_team = CAN\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1967|10|22}}\n| birth_place = [[Scarborough, Toronto|Scarborough]], [[Ontario]], Canada\n| career_start = 1987\n| career_end = 2004\n| draft = 81st overall\n| draft_year = 1986\n| draft_team = [[Quebec Nordiques]]\n| image = \n}}\n'''Ronald Frederick Bradley Tugnutt''' (born October 22, 1967) is a [[Canadian]] former professional [[ice hockey]] [[goaltender]]. He played in the [[National Hockey League]] (NHL) with several teams from [[1987\u201388 NHL season|1987]]\u2013[[2003\u201304 NHL season|2004]] and is formerly the president, governor and head coach of the [[Central Canada Hockey League]]'s [[Kemptville 73's]].<ref>{{cite web |title=PRESS RELEASE - 73'S HAVE NEW OWNERSHIP {{!}} CJHL: Kemptville 73s Jr. A |url=http://cchlkemptville.pointstreaksites.com/view/cchlkemptville/news-424/news_485671 |website=cchlkemptville.pointstreaksites.com |publisher=Kemptville 73\u2019s Jr \u201cA\u201d Hockey Club |accessdate=4 August 2018 |language=en |date=11 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Playing career==\n\n===Early years===\nTugnutt was born in [[Scarborough, Toronto|Scarborough]], [[Ontario]]. As a youth, he played in the 1980 [[Quebec International Pee-Wee Hockey Tournament]] with a [[minor ice hockey]] team from [[Toronto]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.publicationsports.com/ressources/files/439/Joueurs_Pro.pdf|title=Pee-Wee players who have reached NHL or WHA|year=2018|website=Quebec International Pee-Wee Hockey Tournament|access-date=2019-01-16}}</ref>\n\nTugnutt played three seasons with the [[Peterborough Petes]] in the [[Ontario Hockey League]], and won the [[F. W. \"Dinty\" Moore Trophy]] for the rookie with the best [[goals against average]], followed by the [[Dave Pinkney Trophy]] for Top Team Goaltending, and was named to the OHL All Star team in 1987.{{cn|date=January 2019}}\n\n===NHL beginnings===\nHe was drafted by the [[Quebec Nordiques]] in the 4th round (87th overall) of the [[1986 NHL Entry Draft]]. He was primarily used as a backup during his first three pro seasons, bouncing up and down between the [[American Hockey League|AHL]]'s [[Halifax Citadels]] and the parent club in [[Quebec City]]. During [[1990\u201391 NHL season]], Tugnutt played what would be a career high 56 games for Quebec and established himself as a quality NHL starter despite playing for what was then the worst team in the league.\n\nOn March 21, 1991, Tugnutt stopped 70 of 73 shots to earn his team a 3-3 tie against the [[Boston Bruins]], the second highest number of saves made in a regular season game in NHL history. His performance in that game evoked such respect that after it was over, several Bruins players skated over to congratulate Tugnutt.<ref>New York Times, [https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9D0CEFDC1731F930A15750C0A967958260 March 21, 1991]</ref> The hometown Bruins fans gave him a standing ovation after the game ended as well.\n\nIn the midst of an inconsistent [[1991\u201392 NHL season]], and with the emergence of [[St\u00e9phane Fiset]] as the Nordiques' #1 goaltender, Tugnutt was demoted to the Nordiques' AHL affiliate. In exchange for [[Martin Ru\u010d\u00ednsk\u00fd]], he was soon traded to the [[Edmonton Oilers]] to serve as [[Bill Ranford]]'s backup. Tugnutt remained in this role until he was selected by the [[Mighty Ducks of Anaheim]] in the [[1993 NHL Expansion Draft|1993 expansion draft]]. In Anaheim, he split goaltending duties with [[Guy Hebert]].\n\nAs Anaheim quickly decided that Hebert was to be their future starter, and as the [[Montreal Canadiens]] decided that [[Andr\u00e9 Racicot]] and [[Les Kuntar]] were not adequately serving as [[Patrick Roy]]'s backup, Tugnutt was acquired by the [[Montreal Canadiens]] in exchange for [[Stephan Lebeau]]. In his new role, Tugnutt's performance suffered; for Anaheim he posted a .908 save percentage in 28 games. For Montreal, he posted an .860 save percentage in eight games during the [[1993-94 NHL season|1993-94 season]].\n\nDuring the 1994 [[Stanley Cup]] playoffs against the [[Boston Bruins]], Tugnutt started a match as starter Patrick Roy was recuperating from an [[appendectomy]]. He did not return to the Canadiens for the [[1995\u201396 NHL season|1995\u201396 season]], and was replaced by [[Patrick Labrecque]]. These experiences caused Tugnutt to ponder retirement.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tsn.ca/nhl/teams/players/bio/?id=199&hubname=nhl|title=404|website=TSN}}</ref>\n\n===Career breakthrough===\nIn 1995, Tugnutt signed a one-year deal with the [[Washington Capitals]], and subsequently spent the entire 1995-96 season with their AHL affiliate, the [[Portland Pirates]]. He was productive in Portland, helping lead the Pirates to the [[Calder Cup]] Finals.<ref>The AHL.com, [http://www.theahl.com/AHLNews96-97/apr23_ron.html Portland rejuvanates Tugnutt's career]</ref>\n\nIt was this strong performance that caught the attention of the [[Ottawa Senators]]. With the help of goaltending coach [[Phil Myre]], Tugnutt worked on the fundamentals, gained some confidence and improved his game each season. While in Ottawa, he went from fighting for the backup position with [[Mike Bales]] behind starter [[Damian Rhodes]] to splitting duties with Rhodes the next two seasons and becoming the team's undisputed starting goaltender by 1999.\n\nOn April 12, 1997, Tugnutt backstopped the Senators to a 1-0 shutout of the [[Buffalo Sabres]] in the final game of the regular season. Tugnutt's father had just died and immediately following the win Tugnutt pointed to the rafters to signify the win was for his father. The moment was captured by cameras and became an iconic image of Tugnutt. This win propelled the Senators to their first playoff berth.<ref name=\"ottawacitizen.com\">{{cite web|url=https://ottawacitizen.com/sports/hockey/team-tugnutt-relishes-time-together-as-a-hockey-family|title=Team Tugnutt relishes time together as a hockey family (with video)|date=11 November 2014|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIn [[1998\u201399 NHL season|1998\u201399]], Tugnutt had the best season of his career, and one of the best by an NHL goaltender in the modern era. He posted a league-best [[goals against average]] of 1.79, placed second in the league in save percentage at .925, had a career high in wins, and tied a career high in shutouts. This outstanding play, and an injury to [[Curtis Joseph]], gave Tugnutt the opportunity to play in the 1999 [[National Hockey League All-Star Game|NHL All-Star Game]].\n\nThe next season, Rhodes was shipped to the expansion [[Atlanta Thrashers]], giving Tugnutt sole possession of the starting job. However, he was unable to match his previous season and Ottawa decided to trade him to the [[Pittsburgh Penguins]] in favor of an experienced playoff performer, [[Tom Barrasso]].\n\nAfter arriving in Pittsburgh, Tugnutt took over the starting job from [[Jean-S\u00e9bastien Aubin]] and helped lead Pittsburgh deep into the playoffs. Tugnutt was in goal for the May 4, 2000, playoff game against the [[Philadelphia Flyers]]. He made 70 saves on 72 shots.  The 72nd shot was a goal scored by [[Keith Primeau]] of the Flyers at 12:01 of the fifth [[overtime (hockey)|overtime]].  The final score was Philadelphia 2, Pittsburgh 1, after 152:01 minutes, the longest NHL game since the 1930s.\n\nFollowing his performance with Pittsburgh, Tugnutt became one of the most sought after [[free agent]] goaltenders on the market. Both Ottawa and Pittsburgh attempted to re-sign Tugnutt but were unable to match the lucrative contract offered by the expansion [[Columbus Blue Jackets]].<ref>Post-Gazette, [http://www.post-gazette.com/penguins/20000630pens2.asp Sens want Tugnutt Back, Tugnutt hot on free agent market]</ref><ref>Canoe Sports Slam Hockey, [http://www.canoe.ca/HockeyColumbusArchive/jul4_tug.html Tugnutt Signs with Columbus]</ref>\n\nDuring Columbus' inaugural season, Tugnutt was considered their backbone. Tugnutt's 22 wins broke another NHL record for most wins on an [[expansion team]], and his .917 save percentage was among the best in the league.<ref>The Sports Network, [http://www.sportsnetwork.com/default.asp?c=sportsnetwork&page=nhl/misc/canamucio_archive/crashin_net_nov22.htm Tugnutt was the backbone to Columbus]</ref>\n\nThe team's second season was not as impressive as the first. Tugnutt battled injuries and ended up sharing time with young netminder [[Marc Denis]]. GM [[Doug MacLean]] decided that it was time to give Denis the opportunity to be the sole starter on the club, and traded Tugnutt to the [[Dallas Stars]].<ref>HockeyInformer.com, [http://www.hockeyinformer.com/web/fantasy/editorials/editorial1.shtml Denis had potential to be starter]</ref>\n\nTugnutt went to the Dallas Stars in [[2002\u201303 NHL season|2002\u201303]] as the backup to goaltender [[Marty Turco]]. In January 2003, Turco suffered an ankle injury that allowed Tugnutt to start almost 20 straight games. He posted back to back shutouts during that stretch. For the season, he played 31 games and posted a 15-10-5 record along with four shutouts.\n\n[[2003\u201304 NHL season|2003\u201304]] was possibly Tugnutt's toughest in the NHL. From the start of the season to January he only received three starts. He was sent down to the minors for the first time in almost ten years to get some playing time with the [[Utah Grizzlies]]. Just five games in, Tugnutt pulled his groin and was out until after the All Star break.<ref>AllSports.com,[http://www.allsports.com/cgi-bin/showstory.cgi?story_id=47393 Tugnutt pulls groin in minors]</ref> Soon after, he was recalled to the Dallas Stars. After two solid starts, one of which was a shutout, Tugnutt finally got the break he was waiting for as Turco received a four-game suspension.<ref>ESPN, [http://sports.espn.go.com/nhl/news/story?id=1768163 Turco Suspended 4 Games]</ref> He retired following the 2003-04 season.\n\n===Post-retirement===\nAfter the lockout, Tugnutt joined [[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation|CBC]] as a [[color commentator]] for [[Hockey Night in Canada]].<ref>SLAM! Sports, [http://www.canoe.ca/Slam/Hockey/NHL/2005/10/07/1252602-sun.html Tugnutt Joins CBC as Commentator]</ref> From 2008-09 to 2009-10, Tugnutt served as the goaltending coach for the [[Ontario Hockey League|OHL's]] [[Oshawa Generals]]<ref>oshawagenerals.com, [http://www.oshawagenerals.com/Hockey_Staff_live.php Oshawa Generals Hockey Staff] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090814210548/http://www.oshawagenerals.com/Hockey_Staff_live.php |date=2009-08-14 }}</ref> and was a goaltending consultant for the 2010 Canadian World Junior team.<ref>Hockey Canada, [http://www.hockeycanada.ca/index.php/ci_id/63191/ss_id/56000/la_id/1.htm FOURTEEN ELITE UNDER-20 AND UNDER-18 GOALTENDERS TO ATTEND FOURTH ANNUAL HOCKEY CANADA PROGRAM OF EXCELLENCE CAMP IN CALGARY, JUNE 11-14]</ref> Tugnutt's contract with the Generals was not renewed after a major front office shakeup in May 2010.<ref>Oshawa Express, [http://www.oshawaexpress.ca/story2863May122010.html Gens make big change]</ref> Tugnutt joined the Peterborough Petes coaching staff for the 2010-11 season. Tugnutt was a consultant with Hockey Canada until 2013 when that relationship ended. Tugnutt then moved behind the bench of his sons' team the Kemptville 73's.<ref name=\"ottawacitizen.com\"/>\n\n==Off the ice==\nTugnutt is married to wife Lisa, and the couple have two sons, Jacob and Matthew. The family resides on Stoney Lake near [[Peterborough, Ontario]].\n\nTugnutt enjoys boating and traveling. In the summer of 1998, Tugnutt was involved in a severe boating accident. It was suspected that he might miss out on training camp. Tugnutt healed and had the best season of his career, breaking the modern-day NHL record for lowest G.A.A. and coming 2nd in the league in save percentage.<ref>Hockey Goalies, [http://www.hockeygoalies.org/bio/tugnutt.html Tugnutt Profile, and boating accident]</ref>\n\nTugnutt previously owned the [[Kemptville 73's]], a [[Junior ice hockey|Junior \"A\" ice hockey]] team, where he served as head coach, president and governor.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cchlkemptville.pointstreaksites.com/view/cchlkemptville/team-67/management|title=Management - CJHL: Kemptville 73s Jr. A|website=cchlkemptville.pointstreaksites.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://cchlkemptville.pointstreaksites.com/view/cchlkemptville/team-67/hockey-operations|title=Hockey Operations - CJHL: Kemptville 73s Jr. A|website=cchlkemptville.pointstreaksites.com}}</ref><ref name=\"ottawacitizen.com\"/> Tugnutt sold the team to an ownership group led by former teammate [[Jason York]].\n\n==Honours and records==\n* Modern-day record holder for most saves in a regular season game non-loss (stopped 70 of 73 shots in a 3-3 tie with the [[Boston Bruins]]; March 21, 1991).\n* Holds [[Mighty Ducks of Anaheim]] record for most saves in a regular season game with 46, set against the [[Edmonton Oilers]] on November 21, 1993).\n* Tied with [[Dominik Ha\u0161ek]] for Ottawa Senators highest regular season save percentage.\n* Leader in [[save percentage]] for the 1999\u20132000 Playoffs.\n* Holds Pittsburgh Penguins record for highest save percentage in the playoffs.\n* Has Division named in his honour in the FCHL.\n\n==International play==\nAfter a disappointing 4-game sweep in the [[Season structure of the NHL|NHL playoffs]], Tugnutt was more than excited to play for [[Canada men's national ice hockey team|Team Canada]] in the 1999 [[World Hockey Championship]]. The semi-final game was against the [[Czech Republic]] in which Canada lost after the game went undecided in overtime, ending in a shootout. This was Tugnutt's second appearance on Team Canada. He played for them in 1993 as well.<ref>Ottawa Sun, [http://www.canoe.ca/HockeyWorldChampionships99/may14_tug.html Shootout loss to Czechs]</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n===Regular season and playoffs===\n{| border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"text-align:center; width:85%\"\n|- ALIGN=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#e0e0e0\"\n! align=\"center\" colspan=\"3\" bgcolor=\"#ffffff\" |  \n! align=\"center\" rowspan=\"99\" bgcolor=\"#ffffff\" |  \n! align=\"center\" colspan=\"9\" bgcolor=\"#e0e0e0\" | [[Regular season]]\n! align=\"center\" rowspan=\"99\" bgcolor=\"#ffffff\" |  \n! align=\"center\" colspan=\"8\" bgcolor=\"#e0e0e0\" | [[Playoffs]]\n|- ALIGN=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#e0e0e0\"\n! [[Season (sports)|Season]]\n! Team\n! League\n! GP\n! W\n! L\n! T\n! MIN\n! GA\n! [[Shutout#Ice hockey|SO]]\n! [[Goals against average|GAA]]\n! [[save percentage|SV%]]\n! GP\n! W\n! L\n! MIN\n! GA\n! SO\n! GAA\n! SV%\n|-\n| 1983\u201384\n| Toronto Red Wings\n| [[Greater Toronto Hockey League|MTHL]]\n| 34\n|\n|\n|\n| 1690\n| 75\n| 3\n| 2.67\n|\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014 \n| \u2014\n|- bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| 1983\u201384\n| [[Weston Dukes]]\n| [[Metro Junior A Hockey League|MetJHL]]\n| 1\n|\n|\n|\n| 20\n| 2\n| 0\n| 6.00\n|\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014 \n| \u2014\n|-\n| [[1984\u201385 OHL season|1984\u201385]]\n| [[Peterborough Petes]]\n| [[Ontario Hockey League|OHL]]\n| 18\n| 7\n| 4\n| 2\n| 938\n| 59\n| 0\n| 3.77\n|  \n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014 \n| \u2014\n|- bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| [[1985\u201386 OHL season|1985\u201386]]\n| Peterborough Petes\n| OHL\n| 26\n| 18\n| 7\n| 0\n| 1543\n| 74\n| 1\n| 2.88\n|  \n| 3\n| 2\n| 0\n| 133\n| 6\n| 0\n| 2.70\n|  \n|-  \n| [[1986\u201387 OHL season|1986\u201387]]\n| Peterborough Petes\n| OHL\n| 31\n| 21\n| 7\n| 2\n| 1891\n| 88\n| 2\n| 2.79\n|  \n| 6\n| 3\n| 3\n| 374\n| 21\n| 1\n| 3.36\n|  \n|- bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| [[1987\u201388 AHL season|1987\u201388]]\n| [[Fredericton Express]]\n| [[American Hockey League|AHL]]\n| 34\n| 20\n| 9\n| 4\n| 1964\n| 118\n| 1\n| 3.60\n| .890 \n| 4\n| 1\n| 2\n| 204\n| 11\n| 0\n| 3.23\n|  \n|-  \n| [[1987\u201388 NHL season|1987\u201388]]\n| [[Qu\u00e9bec Nordiques]]\n| [[National Hockey League|NHL]]\n| 6\n| 2\n| 3\n| 0\n| 284\n| 16\n| 0\n| 3.38\n| .870\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014 \n| \u2014\n|- bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| [[1988\u201389 AHL season|1988\u201389]]\n| [[Halifax Citadels]]\n| AHL\n| 24\n| 14\n| 7\n| 2\n| 1368\n| 79\n| 1\n| 3.46\n| .897 \n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014 \n| \u2014\n|-  \n| [[1988\u201389 NHL season|1988\u201389]]\n| Qu\u00e9bec Nordiques\n| NHL\n| 26\n| 10\n| 10\n| 3\n| 1367\n| 82\n| 0\n| 3.60\n| .892\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014 \n| \u2014\n|- bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| [[1989\u201390 AHL season|1989\u201390]]\n| Halifax Citadels\n| AHL\n| 6\n| 1\n| 5\n| 0\n| 366\n| 23\n| 0\n| 3.77\n| .900\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014 \n| \u2014\n|-  \n| [[1989\u201390 NHL season|1989\u201390]]\n| Qu\u00e9bec Nordiques\n| NHL\n| 35\n| 5\n| 24\n| 3\n| 1978\n| 152\n| 0\n| 4.61\n| .859\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014 \n| \u2014\n|- bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| [[1990\u201391 AHL season|1990\u201391]]\n| Halifax Citadels\n| AHL\n| 2\n| 0\n| 1\n| 0\n| 100\n| 8\n| 0\n| 4.80\n| .814 \n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014 \n| \u2014\n|-  \n| [[1990\u201391 NHL season|1990\u201391]]\n| Qu\u00e9bec Nordiques\n| NHL\n| 56\n| 12\n| 29\n| 10\n| 3144\n| 212\n| 0\n| 4.04\n